1782900100 · search x1 + search_document x2 + read_document[2,3] · ok · United States v. Chadwick · 109714 · 433 U.S. 1 (1977), docket 75-1721. luggage high-REP / warrant for property in exclusive police control. "By placing personal effects inside a double-locked footlocker, respondents manifested an expectation that the contents would remain free from public examination...There being no exigency, it was unreasonable for the Government to conduct this search without the safeguards a judicial warrant provides" p.11; "a person's expectations of privacy in personal luggage are substantially greater than in an automobile" p.13; SITA-remoteness "Once law enforcement officers have reduced luggage or other personal property not immediately associated with the person of the arrestee to their exclusive control...a search of that property is no longer an incident of the arrest" p.15. treatment=LIMITED by [[California v. Acevedo]] (Chadwick-Sanders container distinction collapsed in auto context). home=[[Automobile Exception]] Limiting/Historical + [[Search Incident to Arrest]] Related
1782900200 · search x1 + search_document x3 · ok · Cardwell v. Lewis · 109069 · 417 U.S. 583 (1974) PLURALITY (Blackmun; Powell concur in result), docket 72-1603. car-exterior examination = no search; reduced vehicle REP. "One has a lesser expectation of privacy in a motor vehicle because its function is transportation...It travels public thoroughfares where both its occupants and its contents are in plain view" p.590; "we fail to comprehend what expectation of privacy was infringed" (tire/paint exterior, public lot) p.591; "where probable cause exists, a warrantless examination of the exterior of a car is not unreasonable" p.592. good law. home=[[Automobile Exception]] Related + [[Two Definitions of Search]] Related. SR-5 homing discordance: queue 2nd-home hint [[Curtilage]] OVERRIDDEN per N1 -> ratio is reduced-vehicle-REP/no-search-of-exterior, homed [[Two Definitions of Search]]
