1782900600 · search x1 + search_document x2 + read_document[0,1] · ok · Cooper v. California · 107360 · 386 U.S. 58 (1967), docket 103 (Black, J.). warrantless search of car held for forfeiture reasonable. "whether a search and seizure is unreasonable within the meaning of the Fourth Amendment depends upon the facts and circumstances of each case" p.59; "the question here is not whether the search was authorized by state law...whether the search was reasonable under the Fourth Amendment...the reason for and nature of the custody may constitutionally justify the search" p.61; "subsequent search of the car...was closely related to the reason petitioner was arrested, the reason his car had been impounded, and the reason it was being retained" p.61; "Under the circumstances of this case, we cannot hold unreasonable...the examination or search of a car validly held by officers for use as evidence in a forfeiture proceeding" p.62. good law (distinguishes Preston). home=[[Automobile Exception]] Related (inventory/forfeiture)
