1782901100 · search x1 (1 transient "MCP server connection lost" -> retried OK same call) + search_document x2 + read_document[3] · ok · Michigan v. Tyler · 109874 · 436 U.S. 499 (1978), docket 76-1608 (Stewart, J.). fire entry + reasonable-time investigation; later entries need warrant. "A burning building clearly presents an exigency of sufficient proportions to render a warrantless entry 'reasonable'...once in a building for this purpose, firefighters may seize evidence of arson that is in plain view" p.509; "officials need no warrant to remain in a building for a reasonable time to investigate the cause of a blaze after it has been extinguished" p.510; summation "an entry to fight a fire requires no warrant...officials may remain there for a reasonable time to investigate the cause of the blaze. Thereafter, additional entries...must be made pursuant to the warrant procedures governing administrative searches" p.511. good law (refined by Clifford). home=[[Community Caretaking and Emergency Aid]] Progeny + [[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Related
1782901200 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[1] · ok · Michigan v. Clifford · 111057 · 464 U.S. 287 (1984) PLURALITY (Powell; Stevens concur-in-judgment=5th vote), docket 82-357. post-fire search needs warrant where privacy interests remain; admin vs criminal warrant by object. "If reasonable privacy interests remain in the fire-damaged property, the warrant requirement applies, and any official entry must be made pursuant to a warrant in the absence of consent or exigent circumstances" p.293; "If the primary object is to determine the cause and origin of a recent fire, an administrative warrant will suffice...If the primary object of the search is to gather evidence of criminal activity, a criminal search warrant may be obtained only on a showing of probable cause" p.294; "the Cliffords retained reasonable privacy interests in their fire-damaged residence and...the postfire investigations were subject to the warrant requirement" p.295. good law (refines Tyler). home=[[Community Caretaking and Emergency Aid]] Limiting + [[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Related
1782901300 · search x1 + read_document[1] · ok · Thompson v. Louisiana · 111282 · 469 U.S. 17 (1984; announced 1985-01-21) PER CURIAM, docket 83-6775. no murder-scene exception (reaffirms Mincey); 2-hr search still needs warrant. "In Mincey v. Arizona...we unanimously rejected the contention that one of the exceptions to the Warrant Clause is a 'murder scene exception'...'the murder scene exception...is inconsistent with the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments...not constitutionally permissible simply because a homicide had recently occurred there.' Mincey is squarely on point" p.21; "A 2-hour general search remains a significant intrusion on petitioner's privacy and therefore may only be conducted subject to the constraints--including the warrant requirement--of the Fourth Amendment" p.21. good law. home=[[Community Caretaking and Emergency Aid]] Related + [[Securing the Scene]] Related. year=1984 (cite/volume) date_decided 1985-01-21 noted
1782901400 · search x1 + read_document[0,1] · ok · Flippo v. West Virginia · 1854815 · 528 U.S. 11 (1999) PER CURIAM, docket 98-8770. no general crime-scene exception. "A warrantless search by the police is invalid unless it falls within one of the narrow and well-delineated exceptions to the warrant requirement...none of which the trial court invoked here" p.13-14; "This position squarely conflicts with Mincey v. Arizona...we rejected any general 'murder scene exception' as 'inconsistent with the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments'...Mincey controls here" p.14 (16-hr search + opened closed briefcase; consent left for remand). good law. home=[[Community Caretaking and Emergency Aid]] Related + [[Securing the Scene]] Related (parallel to Thompson for D5 consistency)
1782901500 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[2] · ok · Ryburn v. Huff · 622303 · 565 U.S. 469 (2012) PER CURIAM, docket 11-208. emergency-aid entry on objectively-reasonable belief of imminent violence + QI. "A reasonable police officer could read these decisions to mean that the Fourth Amendment permits an officer to enter a residence if the officer has a reasonable basis for concluding that there is an imminent threat of violence" p.476; "reasonable police officers in petitioners' position could have come to the conclusion that the Fourth Amendment permitted them to enter the Huff residence if there was an objectively reasonable basis for fearing that violence was imminent...based on the facts as found by the District Court" p.477 (Graham split-second/no-hindsight; reversed 9th Cir denial of QI). good law. home=[[Community Caretaking and Emergency Aid]] Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related
1782901600 · search x1 + get_endpoint_item/clusters x1 + read_document[0],[3,4] · ok · Case v. Montana · IDENTITY CONFIRMED (flagged ingest): SCOTUS No. 24-624, argued Oct 15 2025, DECIDED Jan 14 2026, 607 U.S. ___ (2026); KAGAN J. UNANIMOUS (Sotomayor+Gorsuch concur); petitioner William Trevor Case v. Montana; cert to Mont. S.Ct.; AFFIRMED (judgment not all reasoning) 417 Mont. 354/553 P.3d 985. POST-2015 L3: cluster 10774335 -> lead opinion_id 11240920 (grep "CASE v. MONTANA"/Kagan confirmed). HELD: Brigham City objective-reasonableness for emergency-aid home entry applies WITHOUT FURTHER GLOSS (NOT lowered to Terry reasonable-suspicion; NOT raised to probable cause). "Brigham City did not adopt Terry's reasonable-suspicion standard for home entries...formulated its own standard...'an objectively reasonable basis for believing'" slip op.7; "We decline Case's invitation to put a new probable-cause spin onto Brigham City...we asked simply whether an officer had 'an objectively reasonable basis for believing' that his entry was direly needed to prevent or deal with serious harm" slip op.8; scope-limit "an emergency-aid entry provides no basis to search the premises beyond what is reasonably needed to deal with the emergency" slip op.9; "An officer may enter a home without a warrant if he has 'an objectively reasonable basis for believing that an occupant is seriously injured or imminently threatened with such injury'...The officers' entry satisfied that test" slip op.10-11. good law (LIVE 2026 holding). home=[[Community Caretaking and Emergency Aid]] Key-Progeny (SCOTUS->Key per N5). slip-op pinpoints ^pin-slipN. END Batch D 15/15.
1782901700 · search x1 + search_document x2 + read_document[3] · ok · Go-Bart Importing Co. v. United States · 101643 · 282 U.S. 344 (1931), docket 111 (Butler, J.). SITA may not become general exploratory search. "There is no formula for the determination of reasonableness. Each case is to be decided on its own facts and circumstances" p.357; "made a general and apparently unlimited search, ransacking the desk, safe, filing cases and other parts of the office. It was a lawless invasion of the premises and a general exploratory search in the hope that evidence of crime might be found" p.358 (distinguishes Marron: visible/accessible items in immediate custody OK). good law (foundational; survives in Chimel). home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Historical/Foundational
1782901800 · search x1 + search_document x2 (2 zero-result phrasings -> recovered) + read_document[0] · ok · Agnello v. United States · 100711 · 269 U.S. 20 (1925), docket 6 (Butler, J.). SITA does not reach distant home. "The right without a search warrant contemporaneously to search persons lawfully arrested while committing crime and to search the place where the arrest is made...is not to be doubted" p.30; "But the right does not extend to other places. Frank Agnello's house was several blocks distant from Alba's house, where the arrest was made. When it was entered and searched, the conspiracy was ended and the defendants were under arrest and in custody elsewhere. That search cannot be sustained as an incident of the arrests" p.30-31. good law (foundational; consistent with Chimel). home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Historical/Foundational
1782901900 · search x1 + read_document[0] · ok · Shipley v. California · 107982 · 395 U.S. 818 (1969) PER CURIAM, docket 540 Misc. (decided same day as Chimel). no search of home as incident to arrest made OUTSIDE it. "a search 'can be incident to an arrest only if it is substantially contemporaneous with the arrest and is confined to the immediate vicinity of the arrest'" (quoting Stoner) p.819-820; "the Constitution has never been construed...to allow the police, in the absence of an emergency, to arrest a person outside his home and then take him inside for the purpose of conducting a warrantless search...'one's house cannot lawfully be searched without a search warrant, except as an incident to a lawful arrest therein'" (quoting Agnello 269 U.S. at 32) p.820. good law. home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Related
