1782843354 · search x1 + read_document[0,1] · ok · Vale v. Louisiana · 108183 · 399 U.S. 30 (1970), docket 727 (Stewart, J.; Blackmun NP; Black+Burger dissent). SITA cannot reach a house when arrest is OUTSIDE it; State bears burden of exigency. "only if it is substantially contemporaneous with the arrest and is confined to the immediate vicinity of the arrest" (quoting Shipley) *33; "If a search of a house is to be upheld as incident to an arrest, that arrest must take place inside the house...not somewhere outside" *34; "The burden rests on the State to show the existence of such an exceptional situation" *34; "We decline to hold that an arrest on the street can provide its own exigent circumstance so as to justify a warrantless search of the arrestees house" *35. good law (applies Chimel). home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Limiting / [[Arrest in the Home]] Related. related pruned: dropped Stoner (not yet authored, Batch G).
1782843439 · search x1 + read_document[1,0] · ok · United States v. Edwards · 108995 · 415 U.S. 800 (1974), docket 73-88 (White, J.; Stewart+3 dissent). SITA extends in TIME: clothing taken ~10h after arrest at jail valid. "searches and seizures that could be made on the spot at the time of arrest may legally be conducted later when the accused arrives at the place of detention" *803; "once the accused is lawfully arrested and is in custody, the effects in his possession at the place of detention that were subject to search at the time and place of his arrest may lawfully be searched and seized without a warrant even though a substantial period of time has elapsed" *807; DeLeo quote re privacy out of realm of protection *808-809. good law. home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Progeny. related: Robinson/Chimel/Abel/Lafayette (all exist).
1782843588 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[5] · ok · Virginia v. Moore · 145814 · 553 U.S. 164 (2008), docket 06-1082 (Scalia, J.; Ginsburg concur in judgment). CL copy S.Ct.-paginated. Arrest on PC reasonable under 4A even if it violates state arrest law; SITA follows; no exclusion for state-law-only violation. "warrantless arrests for crimes committed in the presence of an arresting officer are reasonable under the Constitution, and...state restrictions do not alter the Fourth Amendments protections" *1607 (S.Ct.); "officers may perform searches incident to constitutionally permissible arrests" / "search incident to the arrest requires no additional justification" *1607; "When officers have probable cause to believe that a person has committed a crime in their presence, the Fourth Amendment permits them to make an arrest, and to search the suspect" *1608. good law. N1 REFINEMENT: led home with [[Seizure of the Person]] Progeny (central holding = arrest reasonableness) ahead of queue-lead [[Search Incident to Arrest]] Progeny + [[The Exclusionary Rule]] Related (all kept). related Robinson/Atwater/Knowles(this batch)/Devenpeck.
1782843784 · search x1 + search_document x4 · ok · Florence v. Board of Chosen Freeholders of County of Burlington · 626454 · 566 U.S. 318 (2012), docket 10-945 (Kennedy, J., except Part IV; Roberts+Alito concur; Breyer+3 dissent). SLIP OPINION on CL (566 U.S. ___, no embedded reporter pagination) -> pinpoints to published U.S. Reports + Part. jail-intake visual strip search of ALL arrestees entering general population, no individualized suspicion, regardless of minor offense. "a regulation impinging on an inmates constitutional rights must be upheld if it is reasonably related to legitimate penological interests" (Turner) ~326; "substantial interest in preventing any new inmate...even greater risk when he is admitted to the general population" Part IV; "search procedures...struck a reasonable balance between inmate privacy and the needs of the institutions. The Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments do not require adoption of the framework of rules petitioner proposes" ~339. good law (Roberts/Alito cabin to general-population detainees). home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Progeny / [[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Related. alias "Florence v. Board of Chosen Freeholders of County of Burlington". related Lafayette/Maryland v. King/Atwater (Bell v. Wolfish not yet a page - omitted from links).
1782843918 · search x1 + read_document[0,1] · ok · Preston v. United States · 106771 · 376 U.S. 364 (1964), docket 163 (Black, J., unanimous). U.S.-Reports paginated. delayed station/garage car search is NOT SITA (too remote in time/place). "Once an accused is under arrest and in custody, then a search made at another place, without a warrant, is simply not incident to the arrest" *367; "these justifications are absent where a search is remote in time or place from the arrest" *367; "the search was too remote in time or place to have been made as incidental to the arrest...failed to meet the test of reasonableness...rendering the evidence...inadmissible" *368. TREATMENT: good (SITA-remoteness holding intact); auto-exception line (Chambers v. Maroney, Michigan v. Thomas) DISTINGUISHES not overrules -> note added; by=[]. Queue tier-reason good-law CONCORDANT. home=[[Search Incident to Arrest]] Historical / [[Automobile Exception]] Related. related Chambers v. Maroney/Chimel/Agnello/Chadwick.
