1782844308 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[1,3] · ok · Winston v. Lee · 111380 · 470 U.S. 753 (1985), docket 83-1334 (Brennan, J.; Burger concur; Blackmun+Rehnquist concur in judgment). U.S.-Reports paginated. compelled surgery (general anesthesia) to remove bullet = unreasonable under Schmerber balance even w/ warrant+PC. "A compelled surgical intrusion into an individuals body for evidence...may be unreasonable even if likely to produce evidence of a crime" *759; "The reasonableness of surgical intrusions beneath the skin depends on a case-by-case approach, in which the individuals interests in privacy and security are weighed against societys interests" *760; "the Commonwealth has failed to demonstrate that it would be reasonable...to search for evidence of this crime by means of the contemplated surgery" *766; "a more substantial justification is required" *767. good law. N1 PRUNE+FLAG: dropped queue 2nd home [[Search Incident to Arrest]] (NOT a SITA case - separately-warranted surgical bodily search, not incident to arrest). home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Limiting (sole). alias "Lee v. Winston". related Schmerber/Cupp v. Murphy/McNeely.
1782844416 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[1] · ok · United States v. Ventresca · 106990 · 380 U.S. 102 (1965), docket 28 (Goldberg, J.; Douglas dissent). U.S.-Reports paginated; citeCount 4171. commonsense affidavit reading; doubtful cases favor warrant. "affidavits for search warrants...must be tested and interpreted by magistrates and courts in a commonsense and realistic fashion...Technical requirements of elaborate specificity...have no proper place in this area" *108; "the preference accorded police action taken under a warrant" *106-107; "the courts should not invalidate the warrant by interpreting the affidavit in a hypertechnical, rather than a commonsense, manner" *108-109; "the resolution of doubtful or marginal cases in this area should be largely determined by the preference to be accorded to warrants" *109. good law (anchors Gates deferential review / Leon good faith). home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Progeny / [[Probable Cause and Reasonable Suspicion]] Related. related Gates/Aguilar/Brinegar.
1782844529 · search x1 + search_document x2 + read_document[3] · ok · United States v. Harris (1971) · 108379 · 403 U.S. 573 (1971), docket 30 (Burger, C.J., plurality; White joins Part III making penal-interest a holding; Black/Blackmun concur; Harlan+3 dissent). U.S.-Reports paginated; citeCount 1806. statement against penal interest = indicium of informant reliability supporting PC. "Admissions of crime, like admissions against proprietary interests, carry their own indicia of credibility-sufficient at least to support a finding of probable cause to search" *583; "That the informant may be paid or promised a break does not eliminate the residual risk and opprobrium of having admitted criminal conduct" *584; reputation = practical consideration of everyday life *583. TREATMENT good (penal-interest factor survives under Gates totality); Aguilar-Spinelli framework superseded by Illinois v. Gates 1983 -> note; by=[]. YEAR-SUFFIX filename "United States v. Harris (1971).md" + alias "United States v. Harris" (multiple Harris cases: existing Harris v. United States(1968) reversed-pair + famous 1947 SITA Harris v. United States; prudent disambig per prompt+queue). home=[[Probable Cause and Reasonable Suspicion]] Progeny / [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related. related Aguilar/Spinelli/Gates.
