1782844691 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[2] · ok · Stanford v. Texas · 106964 · 379 U.S. 476 (1965), docket 40 (Stewart, J., unanimous). U.S.-Reports paginated. heightened particularity for expressive materials; general warrant for "books...concerning the Communist Party of Texas" void. "the constitutional requirement that warrants must particularly describe the things to be seized is to be accorded the most scrupulous exactitude when the things are books, and the basis for their seizure is the ideas which they contain" *485; "nothing is left to the discretion of the officer executing the warrant" (Marron) *485-486; "The indiscriminate sweep of that language is constitutionally intolerable" *486; Entick/general-warrant *486. good law. home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Progeny (single). related Garrison/Groh/Andresen (Entick v. Carrington Batch-O not-yet-authored -> italic-plain in prose, not linked).
