1782845444 · search x1 + search_document x1 + read_document[2] · ok · Los Angeles County v. Rettele · 145728 (caption "Los Angeles County, California v. Rettele") · 550 U.S. 609 (2007) PER CURIAM, docket 06-605 (Stevens+Ginsburg concur in judgment on QI; Souter would deny cert). CL copy S.Ct.-paginated. brief detention of occupants (naked, out of bed, gunpoint, ~2 min; whole episode <15 min) while securing scene during valid-warrant execution = reasonable; no 4A violation -> no QI inquiry needed. "Deputies were not required to turn their backs to allow Rettele and Sadler to retrieve clothing...The risk of harm...is minimized if the officers routinely exercise unquestioned command of the situation" (Summers) *1993; "no accusation that the detention here was prolonged. The deputies left the home less than 15 minutes after arriving" *1993; "When officers execute a valid warrant and act in a reasonable manner to protect themselves from harm...the Fourth Amendment is not violated" *1993-94; QI: "no necessity for further inquiries concerning qualified immunity" (Saucier) *1994. good law. home=[[Securing the Scene]] Progeny / [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related. alias "Los Angeles County, California v. Rettele". related Summers/Muehler v. Mena/Bailey.
