1782902000 · [S5-B6 #1] search x1 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/101970) x1 + read_document x1 · ok · Sgro v. United States · opinion 101970 · 287 U.S. 206 (1932), No. 55, decided 1932-12-05 (Hughes, C.J.; McReynolds concur; Stone & Cardozo dissent). HOLDING: warrant void if unexecuted within statutory 10 days cannot be revived by redating; reissue = new proceeding requiring fresh contemporaneous PC finding. quotes p.210 "no provision which authorizes the commissioner to extend its life or to revive it"; p.211 "issue of a second warrant is essentially a new proceeding which must have adequate support...These cannot be escaped by describing the action as a reissue"; p.211 "purpose of the statute would be thwarted if by the simple expedient of redating, without more, the time for the execution of a warrant could be extended"; p.212 "took no proof to show that probable cause then existed...simply changed the date of the old warrant." good law (staleness/prompt-execution foundational). home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Progeny(staleness)
1782902400 · [S5-B6 #2] search x1 + read_document[chunk0] x1 + search_document("no special showing") x1 + read_document[chunk4] x1 · ok · Gooding v. United States · opinion 109017 · 416 U.S. 430 (1974), No. 72-6902, decided 1974-04-29 (Rehnquist, J.; Douglas & Marshall dissent). HOLDING: 21 U.S.C. §879(a) governs nighttime narcotics-warrant service (not Rule 41 / DC Code); requires no special showing for a nighttime search other than that contraband is likely on the premises at that time. quotes p.439 "at any time of the day or night...probable cause to believe that grounds exist for the warrant and for its service at such time"; p.458 "21 U.S.C. §879(a) requires no special showing for a nighttime search, other than a showing that the contraband is likely to be on the property or person to be searched at that time"; p.458 application "continuing traffic of drugs...prior purchase through an informer...sufficient to satisfy 21 U.S.C. §879(a)". good law (statutory; statute in force). home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Related(nighttime execution)
1782902800 · [S5-B6 #3] search x1 + search_document("covert entry") x1 + search_document("precise manner...executed") x1 · ok · Dalia v. United States · opinion 110061 · 441 U.S. 238 (1979), No. 77-1722, decided 1979-04-18 (Powell, J.; cert to CA3 575 F.2d 1344). HOLDINGS: (II) 4A does not per se prohibit covert entry to install legal bugging equipment; (III) Title III authorizes courts to approve covert entries though statute silent; (IV) 4A does not require warrant to specify manner of execution / covert entry. quotes p.248 "The Fourth Amendment does not prohibit per se a covert entry performed for the purpose of installing otherwise legal electronic bugging equipment"; p.257 "search warrants [need not] include a specification of the precise manner in which they are to be executed...generally left to the discretion of the executing officers". good law. home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Progeny(manner of execution/covert entry)
1782903200 · [S5-B6 #4] search x1 + search_document("owner...suspected of crime") x1 + search_document("scrupulous exactitude") x1 + read_document[chunk4] x1 · ok · Zurcher v. Stanford Daily · opinion 109876 · 436 U.S. 547 (1978), No. 76-1484, decided 1978-05-31 (White, J.; CL date_filed 1978-10-02 reflects later modification, decision May 31 1978). HOLDING: warrant may search non-suspect third party premises (incl. newspaper) on PC evidence is there; 1A requires warrant requirements applied with "scrupulous exactitude," not subpoena-first. quotes p.556 "critical element...is not that the owner of the property is suspected of crime but that there is reasonable cause to believe that the specific 'things'...are located on the property"; p.564 "requirements of the Fourth Amendment must be applied with 'scrupulous exactitude'". good law (4A holding intact; Privacy Protection Act 1980 §2000aa statutory overlay for press, NOT a constitutional limit). home=[[The Warrant Requirement]] Progeny(third-party premises)
1782903700 · [S5-B6 #5] search x1 + search_document("landlord") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · Chapman v. United States (1961) · opinion 106197 · 365 U.S. 610 (1961), No. 175, decided 1961-04-03 (Whittaker, J.; Frankfurter concur in judgment; Clark dissent). YEAR-SUFFIX collision (real-world same-stem Chapman v. United States 500 U.S. 453 (1991) LSD-weight, not in corpus); file = "Chapman v. United States (1961).md", alias "Chapman v. United States". HOLDING: landlord cannot consent to search of tenant's leased premises; warrantless entry on landlord's authority violates 4A. quotes p.617 (quoting Johnson 333 U.S. 14) "would reduce the [Fourth] Amendment to a nullity and leave [tenants'] homes secure only in the discretion of [landlords]"; p.618 "It follows that this search was unlawful...the judgment of the Court of Appeals must be [reversed]". good law (consistent w/ Matlock, Stoner, Randolph). home=[[Consent Searches]] Progeny(third-party consent)
1782904100 · [S5-B6 #6] search x1 + search_document("night clerk") x1 + search_document("entitled to constitutional protection") x1 · ok · Stoner v. California · opinion 106777 · 376 U.S. 483 (1964), No. 209, decided 1964-03-23 (Stewart, J.). HOLDING: hotel night clerk cannot consent to search of guest's room; only the guest may waive his 4A right; apparent-authority of clerk insufficient. quotes p.490 "a guest in a hotel room is entitled to constitutional protection against unreasonable searches and seizures. That protection would disappear if it were left to depend upon the unfettered discretion of an employee of the hotel"; p.488 "rights protected by the Fourth Amendment are not to be eroded by strained applications of the law of agency or by unrealistic doctrines of 'apparent authority'"; p.489 "right...only the petitioner could waive...no basis whatsoever to believe that the night clerk had been authorized by the petitioner". good law (distinguished, not overruled, by Illinois v. Rodriguez). home=[[Consent Searches]] Progeny(third-party consent/apparent authority)
1782904500 · [S5-B6 #7] search x1 + search_document("claim of lawful authority") x1 + search_document("instinct with coercion") x1 · ok · Bumper v. North Carolina · opinion 107716 · 391 U.S. 543 (1968), No. 1016, decided 1968-06-03 (Stewart, J.). HOLDING: consent invalid where mere acquiescence to officer's claim of lawful authority (false/unsubstantiated claim of warrant); State bears burden of proving voluntariness. quotes p.548-549 "burden of proving that the consent was, in fact, freely and voluntarily given. This burden cannot be discharged by showing no more than acquiescence to a claim of lawful authority"; p.550 "he announces in effect that the occupant has no right to resist the search. The situation is instinct with coercion...Where there is coercion there cannot be consent". good law (carried into Schneckloth). home=[[Consent Searches]] Limiting(voluntariness)
1782904900 · [S5-B6 #8] search x1 + search_document("commercial") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Lewis v. United States (1966) · opinion 107312 · 385 U.S. 206 (1966), No. 36, decided 1966-12-12 (Warren, C.J.; Brennan/Fortas concur; Douglas dissent). YEAR-SUFFIX (real-world same-stem Lewis v. US 445 U.S. 55 (1980) felon-in-possession; 518 U.S. 322 (1996) petty offense — not in corpus); file="Lewis v. United States (1966).md", alias "Lewis v. United States". HOLDING: undercover agent invited into home to buy contraband = no 4A search (misplaced trust); agent may not exceed invitation. quotes p.211 "the home is converted into a commercial center...A government agent...may accept an invitation to do business and may enter upon the premises for the very purposes contemplated by the occupant"; p.211 limit "does not mean...an agent is authorized to conduct a general search" (cites Gouled); p.210 "agent see, hear, or take anything that was not contemplated...by petitioner as a necessary part of his illegal business". good law (false-friend line: Hoffa/Lopez/White). N1 RE-ORDER: home-by-holding = [[Two Definitions of Search]] primary (search-threshold/misplaced trust), [[Consent Searches]] secondary Related (queue had Consent first). home=[[Two Definitions of Search]] Related + [[Consent Searches]] Related
1782905300 · [S5-B6 #9] search x1 + search_document("administrative entry") x1 + search_document("businessman, like the occupant") x1 · ok · See v. City of Seattle · opinion 107474 · 387 U.S. 541 (1967), No. 180, decided 1967-06-05 (White, J.). HOLDING: nonpublic commercial-premises admin inspection generally requires a warrant; businessman may refuse warrantless regulatory entry, cannot be punished. quotes p.543 "The businessman, like the occupant of a residence, has a constitutional right to go about his business free from unreasonable official entries upon his private commercial property"; p.545 "administrative entry, without consent, upon the portions of commercial premises which are not open to the public may only be compelled through prosecution or physical force within the framework of a warrant procedure". good law (companion to Camara; later pervasively-regulated exception Barlow's/Donovan/Biswell/Burger). home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Anchor + [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related
1782905700 · [S5-B6 #10] search x1 + search_document("warrant") x1 + search_document("do not suffice to justify warrantless") x1 · ok · Marshall v. Barlow's, Inc. · opinion 109866 · 436 U.S. 307 (1978), No. 76-1143, decided 1978-05-23 (White, J.). file stem "Marshall v. Barlow's Inc.md" (apostrophe-safe), alias "Marshall v. Barlow's". HOLDING: OSHA §8(a) warrantless workplace-inspection authorization unconstitutional; admin warrant required for ordinary business absent pervasively-regulated exception. quotes p.311 "The Warrant Clause of the Fourth Amendment protects commercial buildings as well as private homes"; p.313 "unless some recognized exception to the warrant requirement applies, See v. Seattle would require a warrant"; p.324 "do not suffice to justify warrantless inspections under OSHA or vitiate the general constitutional requirement that for a search to be reasonable a warrant must be obtained"; p.325 "the Act is unconstitutional insofar as it purports to authorize inspections without warrant or its equivalent". admin-warrant standard < criminal PC. good law. home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Progeny
1782906200 · [S5-B6 #11] search x1 + search_document("pervasively regulated") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 + search_document x2 (expectation of privacy variants) · ok · Donovan v. Dewey · opinion 110530 · 452 U.S. 594 (1981), No. 80-901, decided 1981-06-17 (Marshall, J.; Rehnquist concur; Stewart dissent). HOLDING: warrantless inspections of pervasively-regulated mines under Mine Safety & Health Act §103(a) reasonable; comprehensive scheme (certainty/regularity/frequency/scope) is constitutionally adequate substitute for warrant. quotes p.598-599 "expectation of privacy that the owner of commercial property enjoys...differs significantly from the sanctity accorded an individual's home...adequately protected by regulatory schemes authorizing warrantless inspections"; p.602 "warrantless inspections required by the Mine Safety and Health Act do not offend the Fourth Amendment"; p.603 "certainty and regularity of its application, provides a constitutionally adequate substitute for a warrant. We believe that it does". good law (Colonnade-Biswell line; later Burger 3-part test). home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Progeny
1782906700 · [S5-B6 #12] search x1 + search_document("inspection is to be effective") x1 + search_document x2 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · United States v. Biswell · opinion 108533 · 406 U.S. 311 (1972), No. 71-81, decided 1972-05-15 (White, J.; Blackmun concur in result; Douglas dissent). HOLDING: warrantless inspection of federally licensed firearms dealer under Gun Control Act §923(g) reasonable; pervasively-regulated business, licensee accepts inspection, unannounced inspection essential. quotes p.316 "if inspection is to be effective and serve as a credible deterrent, unannounced, even frequent, inspections are essential...prerequisite of a warrant could easily frustrate inspection"; p.316 "When a dealer chooses to engage in this pervasively regulated business...The dealer is not left to wonder about the purposes of the inspector or the limits of his task"; p.317 "the inspection may proceed without a warrant where specifically authorized by statute. The seizure of respondent's sawed-off rifles was not unreasonable". good law (w/ Colonnade; Donovan, Burger). home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Progeny
1782907300 · [S5-B6 #13] search x1 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/145852 sub_opinions) x1 + search_document x4 · ok · Safford Unified School District #1 v. Redding · cluster 145852 -> lead opinion 145852 (Souter, J.) IDENTITY CONFIRMED in returned text · 557 U.S. 364 (2009), No. 08-479, decided 2009-06-25. HOLDING: strip search of 13yo for prescription/OTC pain pills unreasonable under T.L.O. (intrusion must match suspicion; no danger or reason pills in underwear); officials had QI (right not clearly established). quotes p.376-377 "any indication of danger to the students from the power of the drugs or their quantity, and any reason to suppose that Savana was carrying pills in her underwear...the combination of these deficiencies was fatal to finding the search reasonable"; p.368 "the official who ordered the unconstitutional search is entitled to qualified immunity from liability"; p.374-375 "embarrassing, frightening, and humiliating"; applies T.L.O. 469 U.S. at 341 scope standard. NOTE: opinion text in slip-pagination; used established U.S. Reports pinpoints (368/374-375/376-377). good law. home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related(QI)
1782907900 · [S5-B6 #14] search x1 + search_document x3 (operational realities / reasonableness / work-related misconduct) · ok · O'Connor v. Ortega · opinion 111851 · 480 U.S. 709 (1987), No. 85-530, decided 1987-03-31 (O'Connor, J., PLURALITY; Scalia concur in judgment = controlling 5th vote on reasonableness; Blackmun dissent). [BL borderline-ingest]. HOLDING: public employees may have REP in office/desk/files subject to operational realities; employer work-related searches judged by reasonableness, no warrant/PC. quotes p.717 "Individuals do not lose Fourth Amendment rights merely because they work for the government...The operational realities of the workplace, however, may make some employees' expectations of privacy unreasonable when an intrusion is by a supervisor rather than a law enforcement official"; p.725-726 "public employer intrusions...for noninvestigatory, work-related purposes, as well as for investigations of work-related misconduct, should be judged by the standard of reasonableness under all the circumstances...both the inception and the scope of the intrusion must be reasonable". good law (reaffirmed in Quon 2010). home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Anchor(workplace REP)
1782908500 · [S5-B6 #15] search x1 (2 clusters: 148797 canonical + 6796843 dup) + get_endpoint_item(clusters/148797 sub_opinions) x1 + search_document x4 · ok · City of Ontario v. Quon · cluster 148797 -> lead opinion 148797 (Kennedy, J.; Roberts/Stevens/Thomas/Ginsburg/Breyer/Alito; Stevens & Scalia concur) IDENTITY CONFIRMED · 560 U.S. 746 (2010), No. 08-1332, decided 2010-06-17. [BL borderline-ingest]. HOLDING: govt employer review of employee texts on dept pager reasonable (legitimate work-related purpose + not excessive scope); REP assumed arguendo, not decided; declined broad digital-privacy rules. quotes p.761 "Because the search was motivated by a legitimate work-related purpose, and because it was not excessive in scope, the search was reasonable under the approach of the O'Connor plurality"; p.759 "The judiciary risks error by elaborating too fully on the Fourth Amendment implications of emerging technology before its role in society has become clear". NOTE slip-pagination; used established U.S. Reports pinpoints 759/761. good law (echoed in Riley/Carpenter). home=[[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Progeny(digital workplace REP)
1782909100 · [S5-B6 #16] search x1 + search_document x3 (silver platter / removing the incentive / inadmissible over...timely objection) · ok · Elkins v. United States · opinion 106107 · 364 U.S. 206 (1960), No. 126, decided 1960-06-27 (Stewart, J.; Frankfurter/Clark/Harlan/Whittaker dissent). HOLDING: silver-platter doctrine abolished; state-seized evidence that would violate 4A if federally seized is inadmissible in federal court; exclusionary rule's purpose is deterrence. quotes p.208 "we conclude that this [silver platter] doctrine can no longer be accepted"; p.217 "The rule is calculated to prevent, not to repair. Its purpose is to deter—to compel respect for the constitutional guaranty in the only effectively available way—by removing the incentive to disregard it"; p.223 "evidence obtained by state officers during a search which, if conducted by federal officers, would have violated the defendant's immunity...is inadmissible over the defendant's timely objection in a federal criminal trial". good law (Mapp 1961 mooted silver-platter; deterrence rationale foundational). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Anchor
1782909500 · [S5-B6 #17] search x1 + read_document(full) x1 · ok · Silverthorne Lumber Co. v. United States · opinion 99506 · 251 U.S. 385 (1920), No. 358, decided 1920-01-26 (Holmes, J.; White C.J. & Pitney dissent). HOLDING: origin of fruit-of-poisonous-tree AND independent-source; illegally obtained evidence may not be used at all, directly or indirectly; gov't may not exploit knowledge from its own wrong; but facts from independent source may be proved. quotes p.392 "not merely evidence so acquired shall not be used before the Court but that it shall not be used at all"; p.392 "If knowledge of them is gained from an independent source they may be proved like any others, but the knowledge gained by the Government's own wrong cannot be used by it in the way proposed"; p.392 "It reduces the Fourth Amendment to a form of words". good law (foundational; Nardone/Wong Sun/Murray). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Anchor
1782909900 · [S5-B6 #18] search x1 + read_document(full) x1 · ok · Nardone v. United States · opinion 103259 · 308 U.S. 338 (1939), No. 240, decided 1939-12-11 (Frankfurter, J.; McReynolds dissent; Reed not part) = "Nardone II" (distinct from Nardone I 302 U.S. 379 (1937)). HOLDING: coined "fruit of the poisonous tree" + recognized attenuation; bars derivative use of illegally obtained evidence; accused may prove substantial part of case was fruit of poisonous tree; gov't may show independent origin / taint attenuated. quotes p.340-341 "the knowledge gained by the Government's own wrong cannot be used by it...simply because it is used derivatively" (quoting Silverthorne 251 U.S. 392); p.341 "the accused to prove that a substantial portion of the case against him was a fruit of the poisonous tree...independent origin"; p.341 "such connection may have become so attenuated as to dissipate the taint". good law (statutory §605 but doctrine carried into 4A via Wong Sun, Brown v. Illinois). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Anchor(attenuation). === BATCH 6 COMPLETE: 18/18 authored, 0 escalations, serial single-lane, 0 transient errors. ===
1782980000 · [S5-B7 #1] search x1 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/109816 sub_opinions) x1 + search_document("greater reluctance") x1 + read_document[chunk3] x1 · ok · United States v. Ceccolini · cluster 109816 -> lead opinion 109816 IDENTITY CONFIRMED in returned text · 435 U.S. 268 (1978), No. 76-1151, decided 1978-03-21 (Rehnquist, J.; Burger concur in judgment; Marshall & Brennan dissent; Blackmun took no part). HOLDING: live-witness testimony far less readily suppressed as fruit than inanimate evidence; exclusionary rule invoked with "much greater reluctance" where the fruit is a willing live witness; attenuation weighs witness free will, non-use of illegal evidence in questioning, time elapsed, officer purpose. quotes *280 "the exclusionary rule should be invoked with much greater reluctance where the claim is based on a causal relationship between a constitutional violation and the discovery of a live witness than when a similar claim is advanced to support suppression of an inanimate object"; *279-280 "The evidence indicates overwhelmingly that the testimony given by the witness was an act of her own free will in no way coerced or even induced by official authority as a result of Biro's discovery of the policy slips"; *280 "The cost of permanently silencing Hennessey is too great for an evenhanded system of law enforcement to bear...negligible deterrent effect". good law (Wong Sun/Nardone attenuation line; modern Strieff). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Progeny(attenuation) (single; queue concordant).
1782980400 · [S5-B7 #2] search x1 + search_document("independent of any official misconduct"->0; "independent source"->4; "three distinct elements"->1) x3 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · United States v. Crews · cluster 110230 -> lead/combined opinion 110230 (Brennan, J., except Part II-D; Powell & White concur) IDENTITY CONFIRMED · 445 U.S. 463 (1980), No. 78-777, decided 1980-03-25. HOLDING: victim's in-court ID not a suppressible fruit of defendant's illegal arrest where its three elements (victim presence, ability to reconstruct/identify, defendant's own presence) have an independent source antedating the misconduct. quotes *471 "A victim's in-court identification of the accused has three distinct elements...none of these three elements 'has been come at by exploitation' of the violation of the defendant's Fourth Amendment rights" (quoting Wong Sun 371 U.S. 488); *472 victim's presence "not traceable to any Fourth Amendment violation...identity was known long before there was any official misconduct"; *473 "the victim's capacity to identify her assailant in court neither resulted from nor was biased by the unlawful police conduct committed long after she had developed that capacity"; *474 defendant cannot "claim immunity from prosecution simply because his appearance in court was precipitated by an unlawful arrest". NB pretrial photo+lineup IDs conceded suppressible; only in-court ID at issue. good law. home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Progeny(independent source) + [[Eyewitness Identification]] Related (queue concordant).
1782980800 · [S5-B7 #3] search x1 + search_document("intrudes so severely") x1 + read_document[chunk4] x1 · ok · Dunaway v. New York · cluster 110096 -> lead/combined opinion 110096 (Brennan, J.; White & Stevens concur; Rehnquist & Burger dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (decides Q reserved in Morales: custodial questioning on less than PC) · 442 U.S. 200 (1979), No. 78-5066, decided 1979-06-05. HOLDING: involuntary transport+station-house detention for custodial interrogation on less than PC is a seizure tantamount to arrest requiring PC (no Terry-balancing); resulting confession is fruit of the illegal seizure, NOT attenuated by Miranda warnings alone; voluntariness only "threshold," then Brown v. Illinois factors govern. quotes *216 "detention for custodial interrogation-regardless of its label-intrudes so severely on interests protected by the Fourth Amendment as necessarily to trigger the traditional safeguards against illegal arrest...the Rochester police violated the Fourth and Fourteenth Amendments when, without probable cause, they seized petitioner and transported him to the police station for interrogation"; *217 "Miranda warnings, and the exclusion of a confession made without them, do not alone sufficiently deter a Fourth Amendment violation" (quoting Brown 422 U.S. 601); *218 Brown factors "temporal proximity...intervening circumstances...purpose and flagrancy of the official misconduct"; *218 application "seized without probable cause in the hope that something might turn up...without any intervening event of significance". good law (foundational; Kaupp per curiam applies it). home=[[Seizure of the Person]] Key—Progeny + [[The Exclusionary Rule]] Related + [[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Related (N1: lead=seizure-threshold holding; queue concordant, triple home retained).
1782981400 · [S5-B7 #4] search x1 + search_document("break the causal connection") x1 [TRANSIENT: first search_document hit "Anthropic proxy: MCP server connection lost" (NOT old-5/min throttle, no "Request was throttled"); per RUNBOOK §3 did non-CL awk spacer + backoff, RETRIED within turn -> OK; lane recovered] + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Taylor v. Alabama · cluster 110760 -> lead/combined opinion 110760 (Marshall, J.; O'Connor/Burger/Powell/Rehnquist dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED ("whether petitioner's confession should have been suppressed as the fruit of an illegal arrest...inconsistent with Dunaway and Brown") · 457 U.S. 687 (1982), No. 81-5152, decided 1982-06-23. HOLDING: confession after warrantless arrest w/o PC suppressed as fruit; ~6hr gap + 3x Miranda + girlfriend visit + ex parte warrant (built on illegally-taken fingerprints, themselves fruit per Davis v. Mississippi) did NOT attenuate; State failed burden. quotes *690 "a confession obtained through custodial interrogation after an illegal arrest should be excluded unless intervening events break the causal connection...sufficiently an act of free will to purge the primary taint" (quoting Brown 422 U.S. 602 / Wong Sun); *690 voluntariness "merely a threshold requirement"; Miranda not a "talisman that cured all Fourth Amendment violations...form of words"; *691 "Petitioner was arrested without probable cause in the hope that something would turn up, and he confessed shortly thereafter without any meaningful intervening event"; *693 fingerprints "themselves the fruit of petitioner's illegal arrest". good law. N1 PRUNE+FLAG: dropped queue 2nd home [[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] (MISMATCH - holding is 4A fruits/attenuation; confession conceded 5A-voluntary, case teaches voluntariness != attenuation, NOT a voluntariness rule). RE-HOMED 2nd to [[Seizure of the Person]] (illegal-arrest ratio, parallel to siblings Dunaway/Kaupp/Brown). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Progeny(attenuation) + [[Seizure of the Person]] Related.
1782982000 · [S5-B7 #5] search x1 + search_document("submission to a claim of lawful authority") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Kaupp v. Texas · cluster/opinion 127919 PER CURIAM IDENTITY CONFIRMED ("confession obtained by exploitation of an illegal arrest") · 538 U.S. 626 (2003), No. 02-5636, decided 2003-05-05. HOLDING: 3am removal of 17yo from bed, handcuffed/in underwear, transported to scene+station for interrogation w/o PC = arrest requiring PC; "Okay" = mere submission not consent (objective test; safety rationale + non-resistance irrelevant); confession suppressed unless State proves taint purged (remand). quotes *630 "Such involuntary transport to a police station for questioning is 'sufficiently like arres[t] to invoke the traditional rule that arrests may constitutionally be made only on probable cause'" (quoting Hayes 470 U.S. 816); *631 "A 17-year-old boy was awakened in his bedroom at three in the morning by at least three police officers...taken out in handcuffs, without shoes, dressed only in his underwear in January...even more starkly than the facts in Dunaway"; *631 "'Okay'...no showing of consent...a mere submission to a claim of lawful authority" (Royer 497); *632-633 "well-established precedent requires suppression of the confession unless that confession was 'an act of free will [sufficient] to purge the primary taint of the unlawful invasion'" (Wong Sun 486), burden on State. good law. home=[[Seizure of the Person]] Key—Progeny + [[The Exclusionary Rule]] Related + [[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Related (queue concordant, triple home; N1 lead=arrest/seizure holding).
1782982600 · [S5-B7 #6] search x1 + search_document("core of the Fourth Amendment") x1 + search_document("does not forbid the admission of evidence") x1 · ok · Wolf v. Colorado · cluster/combined opinion 104709 (Frankfurter, J.; Black concur; Douglas/Murphy/Rutledge dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED · 338 U.S. 25 (1949), Nos. 17 & 18, decided 1949-06-27. FOIL. HOLDING (two parts): (1) 4A's core security against arbitrary police intrusion enforceable vs States via 14A Due Process [SURVIVED]; (2) Weeks exclusionary rule NOT commanded of the States [OVERRULED by Mapp]. quotes *27-28 "The security of one's privacy against arbitrary intrusion by the police-which is at the core of the Fourth Amendment-is basic to a free society. It is therefore implicit in 'the concept of ordered liberty' and as such enforceable against the States through the Due Process Clause"; *33 "in a prosecution in a State court for a State crime the Fourteenth Amendment does not forbid the admission of evidence obtained by an unreasonable search and seizure". TREATMENT = OVERRULED on remedy by Mapp v. Ohio 367 U.S. 643 (1961); authority_weight = Historical (tier 6, N2 overruled-shown-as-history); by=[[Mapp v. Ohio]]. incorporation half survived. home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Historical(overruled by Mapp on remedy) (single; queue concordant). related Mapp/Weeks/Elkins (Rochin v. California pruned-MISSING page).
1782983200 · [S5-B7 #7] search x1 (2 clusters: canonical 218926 + Lexis-dup 7345713) + search_document(218926 "objectively reasonable reliance..."->0; 218926 "binding appellate precedent"->7) x2 + search_document(7263677 lexis "objectively reasonable reliance"->5; "reasonable officer would and should act"->1) x2 · ok · Davis v. United States (2011) · canonical cluster/combined opinion 218926 (Alito, J.; Sotomayor concur in judgment; Breyer & Ginsburg dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (good-faith reliance on Belton-era 11th Cir precedent; Breyer dissent cites Gant) · 564 U.S. 229 (2011), No. 09-11328, decided 2011-06-16. YEAR-SUFFIX REQUIRED collision w/ existing "Davis v. United States.md" (1994 Miranda invocation); file="Davis v. United States (2011).md"; NO bare alias (bare stem already owned by 1994 page -> bare [[Davis v. United States]] resolves to 1994; 2011 reached via year-suffixed stem). HOLDING: exclusionary rule inapplicable to a search conducted in objectively reasonable reliance on binding appellate precedent later overruled (no culpable misconduct to deter). NB combined opinion 218926 is SLIP-paginated (Ante,at-1 refs); used Lexis copy 7263677 [564 U.S. NNN] brackets for U.S.-Reports pinpoints. quotes 564 U.S. 232 "we hold that searches conducted in objectively reasonable reliance on binding appellate precedent are not subject to the exclusionary rule"; 564 U.S. 249-250 "when the police conduct a search in objectively reasonable reliance on binding appellate precedent, the exclusionary rule does not apply...affirmed"; 241 "act as a reasonable officer would and should act" (restated in Application, not quoted - exact U.S. page not bracketed in returned text, kept clean per L1). good law (extends Leon/Krull/Herring). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Progeny(good faith) (single; queue concordant).
1782983800 · [S5-B7 #8] search x1 + search_document("supervisory power does not authorize") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · United States v. Payner · cluster/combined opinion 110317 (Powell, J.; Burger concur; Marshall/Brennan/Blackmun dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED ("whether the District Court properly suppressed the fruits of an unlawful search that did not invade the respondent's Fourth Amendment rights") · 447 U.S. 727 (1980), No. 78-1729, decided 1980-06-23. HOLDING: federal supervisory power may NOT suppress evidence seized unlawfully from a third party (IRS "briefcase caper" vs banker Wolstencroft) at instance of defendant lacking 4A standing; standing limits (Rakas/Alderman) cannot be circumvented via supervisory power even given deliberate/flagrant Gov't misconduct. quotes *735 "the supervisory power does not authorize a federal court to suppress otherwise admissible evidence on the ground that it was seized unlawfully from a third party not before the court...the interest in deterring illegal searches does not justify the exclusion of tainted evidence at the instance of a party who was not the victim of the challenged practices" (Rakas 439 U.S. 137; Alderman 394 U.S. 174-175); *736 "The values assigned to the competing interests do not change because a court has elected to analyze the question under the supervisory power instead of the Fourth Amendment"; *737 "confer on the judiciary discretionary power to disregard the considered limitations of the law it is charged with enforcing...does not extend so far". good law. home=[[Standing to Challenge a Search]] Key—Progeny (single; queue concordant). Stone v. Powell pruned-MISSING.
1782984400 · [S5-B7 #9] search x1 + search_document("coconspirator exception") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · United States v. Padilla · cluster/opinion 112856 PER CURIAM IDENTITY CONFIRMED (rejects 9th Cir "coconspirator exception") · 508 U.S. 77 (1993), No. 92-207, decided 1993-05-03. HOLDING: no coconspirator exception to 4A standing; supervisory role / joint control over conspiracy property does NOT confer standing; only personal privacy or property interest invaded does. quotes *82 (quoting Alderman 394 U.S. 171-172) "suppression of the product of a Fourth Amendment violation can be successfully urged only by those whose rights were violated by the search itself, not by those who are aggrieved solely by the introduction of damaging evidence. Co-conspirators and codefendants have been accorded no special standing"; *82 "Expectations of privacy and property interests govern the analysis...Participants in a criminal conspiracy may have such expectations or interests, but the conspiracy itself neither adds to nor detracts from them"; roles (communication link / in charge of transportation) "no bearing on their respective Fourth Amendment rights"; remanded for individualized interest determinations. good law. home=[[Standing to Challenge a Search]] Key—Progeny (single; queue concordant).
1782985000 · [S5-B7 #10] search x1 + search_document("personal rights which") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Alderman v. United States · cluster/combined opinion 107872 (White, J.; Harlan & Fortas concur/dissent in part) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (electronic surveillance + standing) · 394 U.S. 165 (1969), No. 133, decided 1969-03-10. ANCHOR. HOLDING: 4A standing is personal; only one whose own rights were violated by the search/surveillance may suppress; coconspirators/codefendants no special standing; also ordered disclosure of surveillance records of defendant's own conversations/premises for adversary hearing. quotes *171-172 "suppression of the product of a Fourth Amendment violation can be successfully urged only by those whose rights were violated by the search itself, not by those who are aggrieved solely by the introduction of damaging evidence. Coconspirators and codefendants have been accorded no special standing"; *174 "Fourth Amendment rights are personal rights which, like some other constitutional rights, may not be vicariously asserted"; *174 "There is no necessity to exclude evidence against one defendant in order to protect the rights of another". good law (Rakas 1978 recast standing as substantive REP merits but REAFFIRMED personal-rights principle; not overruled). home=[[Standing to Challenge a Search]] Key—Anchor (single; queue concordant). related Rakas/Jones v. US/Mancusi(this batch)/Simmons(this batch)/Payner(this batch).
1782985600 · [S5-B7 #11] search x1 + search_document("could reasonably have expected") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Mancusi v. DeForte · cluster/combined opinion 107745 (Harlan, J.; Black/Stewart & White dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Teamsters VP DeForte, search of union office, standing) · 392 U.S. 364 (1968), No. 844, decided 1968-06-17. HOLDING: union official has 4A standing/REP in office shared with other officials; capacity to claim 4A depends on REP in area, not property right (applies Katz to standing); warrantless seizure on bare DA subpoena unreasonable. quotes *368 "capacity to claim the protection of the Amendment depends not upon a property right in the invaded place but upon whether the area was one in which there was a reasonable expectation of freedom from governmental intrusion" (Katz 389 U.S. 352); *369 "We hold that in these circumstances DeForte had Fourth Amendment standing to object to the admission of the papers at his trial"; *369 "DeForte still could reasonably have expected that only those persons and their personal or business guests would enter the office, and that records would not be touched except with their permission or that of union higher-ups". good law (workplace-REP result survives; Rakas 1978 abandoned broad 'legitimately on premises' Jones formula + recast standing as substantive REP, but did NOT disturb this holding; underlies O'Connor v. Ortega). home=[[Standing to Challenge a Search]] Key—Progeny (single; queue concordant).
1782986200 · [S5-B7 #12] search x1 + search_document("very substantial likelihood of irreparable misidentification") x1 + search_document("may not thereafter be admitted against him at trial") x1 + read_document[chunks 1,3] x1 · ok · Simmons v. United States · cluster/combined opinion 107636 (Harlan, J.; Black & White concur/dissent in part; Marshall took no part) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (armed robbery; photo-ID suggestiveness + suppression-testimony) · 390 U.S. 377 (1968), No. 55, decided 1968-03-18. TWO HOLDINGS: (1) photo-array due-process standard; (2) suppression-hearing standing testimony immunized at trial-on-guilt. quotes *384 "convictions based on eyewitness identification at trial following a pretrial identification by photograph will be set aside on that ground only if the photographic identification procedure was so impermissibly suggestive as to give rise to a very substantial likelihood of irreparable misidentification"; *394 "we find it intolerable that one constitutional right should have to be surrendered in order to assert another. We therefore hold that when a defendant testifies in support of a motion to suppress evidence on Fourth Amendment grounds, his testimony may not thereafter be admitted against him at trial on the issue of guilt unless he makes no objection". Application: Simmons claim failed (well-lit bank, 5min view, 6+ photos next day, no suggestion -> affirmed); Garrett's suitcase-ownership suppression testimony immunized -> reversed. star pages *384/*394 CONFIRMED via chunk read. good law (Simmons standard -> Biggers/Manson; testimony immunity intact). N6 ELEVATION: queue had [[Standing]] as Related; homed BOTH as Key (each holding genuinely central on its doctrine page). home=[[Eyewitness Identification]] Key—Progeny + [[Standing to Challenge a Search]] Key—Progeny.
1782986800 · [S5-B7 #13] search x1 + search_document("shield against contradiction") x1 + read_document(full) x1 · ok · Walder v. United States · cluster/combined opinion 105188 (Frankfurter, J.; Black & Douglas dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (narcotics; suppressed heroin used to impeach) · 347 U.S. 62 (1954), No. 121, decided 1954-02-01. HOLDING: impeachment exception ORIGIN - illegally seized evidence (inadmissible in case in chief) may impeach a defendant who on his OWN DIRECT makes a sweeping affirmative assertion beyond denying the charged offense; exclusionary rule is a shield, not a license for perjury; door must be opened by defendant's direct (Agnello distinguished - gov't may not smuggle via its own cross). quotes *65 "the defendant can turn the illegal method...to his own advantage, and provide himself with a shield against contradiction of his untruths. Such an extension of the Weeks doctrine would be a perversion of the Fourth Amendment"; *65 "He must be free to deny all the elements of the case against him without thereby giving leave to the Government to introduce by way of rebuttal evidence illegally secured by it...there is hardly justification for letting the defendant affirmatively resort to perjurious testimony in reliance on the Government's disability to challenge his credibility"; *66 Agnello contrast. good law (extended Harris v. New York/Havens; cabined James v. Illinois). N1 ROLE: queue had "Related"; ELEVATED to Key—Anchor(impeachment exception) (originates the doctrine). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Anchor(impeachment exception). Harris v. New York pruned-MISSING (Batch L).
1782987400 · [S5-B7 #14] search x1 + search_document("reasonably suggested by the defendant's direct examination") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · United States v. Havens · cluster/combined opinion 110267 (White, J.; Brennan/Marshall/Stewart/Stevens dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (suppressed T-shirt used to impeach false trial testimony given on cross) · 446 U.S. 620 (1980), No. 79-305, decided 1980-05-27. HOLDING: impeachment exception extends to false statements first elicited on CROSS-examination that is reasonably suggested by defendant's direct; illegally seized evidence may impeach but not be substantive proof of guilt. quotes *627 "we see no difference of constitutional magnitude between the defendant's statements on direct examination and his answers to questions put to him on cross-examination that are plainly within the scope of the defendant's direct examination"; *627-628 "we...hold that a defendant's statements made in response to proper cross-examination reasonably suggested by the defendant's direct examination are subject to otherwise proper impeachment by the government, albeit by evidence that has been illegally obtained and that is inadmissible on the government's direct case, or otherwise, as substantive evidence of guilt". Application: Havens' direct denial of "that kind of activity with McLeroth" opened the T-shirt cross; 5th Cir's direct-only rule rejected. good law (extends Walder; James v. Illinois declines to extend to other defense witnesses). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Progeny(impeachment exception) (single; queue concordant). Harris v. New York/Oregon v. Hass not linked (MISSING/no page).
1782988000 · [S5-B7 #15] search x1 + search_document("decline to extend"->0; "deterrent effect"->7) x2 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · James v. Illinois · cluster/combined opinion 112350 (Brennan, J.; Stevens concur; Kennedy/Rehnquist/O'Connor/Scalia dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (impeachment exception not extended to all defense witnesses) · 493 U.S. 307 (1990), No. 88-6075, decided 1990-01-10. HOLDING: impeachment exception confined to defendant's OWN testimony; prosecution may NOT use illegally obtained evidence to impeach OTHER defense witnesses (would chill calling witnesses + significantly weaken deterrence). Facts: James' illegally-obtained statements (dyed reddish->black hair) used to impeach defense witness Henderson -> reversed. quotes *313-314 "expanding the class of impeachable witnesses from the defendant alone to all defense witnesses...would not promote the truth-seeking function to the same extent...and yet it would significantly undermine the deterrent effect of the general exclusionary rule"; *317 "defendants ought not be able to 'pervert' the exclusion...into a shield for perjury, but it seems no more appropriate for the State to brandish such evidence as a sword with which to dissuade defendants from presenting a meaningful defense through other witnesses...does not apply to other witnesses with equal force"; *320 "we hold that the Illinois Supreme Court erred...use of illegally obtained statements to impeach a defense witness' testimony...reversed". good law (limits Walder/Havens). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Limiting(impeachment exception) (single; queue concordant). Harris v. New York pruned-MISSING.
1782988600 · [S5-B7 #16] search(full name->0) x1 + search(citation 524 U.S. 357->4) x1 + search_document("declined to extend the exclusionary rule") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Pennsylvania Board of Probation and Parole v. Scott · cluster/combined opinion 118235 (Thomas, J.; Rehnquist/O'Connor/Scalia/Kennedy; Stevens & Souter/Ginsburg/Breyer dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED ("whether the exclusionary rule...applies in parole revocation hearings. We hold that it does not."; respondent Keith M. Scott) · 524 U.S. 357 (1998), No. 97-581, decided 1998-06-22. CL caption "Pennsylvania Bd. of Probation and Parole v. Scott" -> alias; title uses full "Board" form (queue stem). NO collision w/ Scott v. Harris (distinct stem). HOLDING: federal exclusionary rule does NOT bar evidence at parole-revocation hearings (prudential cost-benefit; minimal marginal deterrence vs flexible administrative nature). quotes *363 "a Fourth Amendment violation is 'fully accomplished' by the illegal search or seizure, and no exclusion of evidence from a judicial or administrative proceeding can 'cure the invasion of the defendant's rights which he has already suffered'" (Leon 906); *363 "applies only in contexts 'where its remedial objectives are thought most efficaciously served'...repeatedly declined to extend the exclusionary rule to proceedings other than criminal trials"; *364 "We therefore hold that the federal exclusionary rule does not bar the introduction at parole revocation hearings of evidence seized in violation of parolees' Fourth Amendment rights". good law (Calandra/Janis/Lopez-Mendoza line). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Limiting + [[Special Needs and Administrative Searches]] Related (queue concordant). INS v. Lopez-Mendoza/Stone v. Powell mentioned-not-linked (MISSING).
1782989200 · [S5-B7 #17] search x1 + search_document("outweighs the societal costs imposed by the exclusion") x1 + read_document[chunk3] x1 · ok · United States v. Janis · cluster/combined opinion 109539 (Blackmun, J.; Brennan/Marshall & Stewart dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (state-seized evidence in federal civil wagering-tax proceeding) · 428 U.S. 433 (1976), No. 74-958, decided 1976-07-06. HOLDING: exclusionary rule does NOT bar state-officer-unlawfully-seized evidence in a federal civil (tax) proceeding; intersovereign marginal deterrence does not outweigh substantial social costs. quotes *454 "the additional marginal deterrence provided by forbidding a different sovereign from using the evidence in a civil proceeding surely does not outweigh the cost to society of extending the rule to that situation. If, on the other hand, the exclusionary rule does not result in appreciable deterrence, then, clearly, its use in the instant situation is unwarranted"; *454 "exclusion from federal civil proceedings of evidence unlawfully seized by a state criminal enforcement officer has not been shown to have a sufficient likelihood of deterring the conduct of the state police so that it outweighs the societal costs imposed by the exclusion. This Court, therefore, is not justified in so extending the exclusionary rule". state officer already deterred by state+federal criminal exclusion. good law (Calandra/Leon/Scott line). home=[[The Exclusionary Rule]] Key—Limiting (single; queue concordant). INS v. Lopez-Mendoza/Stone v. Powell mentioned-not-linked (MISSING).
1782989800 · [S5-B7 #18] search x1 + search_document("unfettered exercise of his own will") x1 + read_document[chunks 1,2] x1 · ok · Malloy v. Hogan · cluster/combined opinion 106862 (Brennan, J.; Harlan/Clark & White/Stewart dissent) IDENTITY CONFIRMED (reconsiders Twining/Adamson; 5A privilege vs States) · 378 U.S. 1 (1964), No. 110, decided 1964-06-15. HOLDING: 5A privilege against self-incrimination incorporated vs States via 14A by SAME standard as federal (overrules Twining/Adamson on this point); no "watered-down" version. quotes *6 "We hold today that the Fifth Amendment's exception from compulsory self-incrimination is also protected by the Fourteenth Amendment against abridgment by the States"; *8 "The Fourteenth Amendment secures against state invasion the same privilege that the Fifth Amendment guarantees against federal infringement-the right of a person to remain silent unless he chooses to speak in the unfettered exercise of his own will, and to suffer no penalty...for such silence"; *10-11 not "a 'watered-down, subjective version of the individual guarantees of the Bill of Rights'". good law (foundational; predicate for Miranda; harmonized confession-voluntariness w/ 5A; cites Mapp overruling Wolf). home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Key—Anchor + [[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Related (queue concordant). Twining/Adamson/Griffin v. California mentioned-not-linked (MISSING). === BATCH 7 COMPLETE: 18/18 authored, 0 escalations, single serial CL lane throughout. ===
1782950400 · [S5-B8 #1] search(Corley v. United States, 556 U.S. 303) x1 + search_document("without supplanting it") x1 + search_document("prompt presentment") x1 + read_document[chunk1,chunk5] x2 · ok · Corley v. United States · opinion 145888 · 556 U.S. 303 (2009), No. 07-10441, decided 2009-04-06 (Souter, J.; Alito, J. dissenting). HOLDING: 18 U.S.C. §3501 modified but did not supplant McNabb-Mallory; federal confession before presentment & beyond 6 hrs must be suppressed if presentment delay unreasonable/unnecessary. quotes p.309 "the rule known simply as McNabb-Mallory 'generally render[s] inadmissible confessions made during periods of detention that violat[e] the prompt presentment requirement of Rule 5(a)'" (quoting Alvarez-Sanchez 511 U.S. 350, 354); p.322 "We hold that §3501 modified McNabb-Mallory without supplanting it...If the confession occurred before presentment and beyond six hours...the court must decide whether delaying that long was unreasonable or unnecessary...and if it was, the confession is to be suppressed". good law (federal Rule 5(a)/§3501 rule, not constitutional/states). home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny; [[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Related
1782950760 · [S5-B8 #2] search(Rogers v. Richmond, 365 U.S. 534) x1 + search_document("disregard...spoke the truth") x1 + search_document("accusatorial and not an inquisitorial") x1 · ok · Rogers v. Richmond · opinion 106192 · 365 U.S. 534 (1961), No. 40, decided 1961-03-20 (Frankfurter, J.). HOLDING: confession voluntariness under Due Process turns solely on coercion overbearing the will; probable truth/reliability is irrelevant; a voluntariness standard that weighs reliability is constitutionally invalid. quotes p.540-541 "convictions following the admission...of confessions which are involuntary, i.e., the product of coercion...cannot stand. This is so not because such confessions are unlikely to be true but because the methods used to extract them offend an underlying principle...that ours is an accusatorial and not an inquisitorial system"; p.544 "question whether the behavior of the State's law enforcement officials was such as to overbear petitioner's will...a question to be answered with complete disregard of whether or not petitioner in fact spoke the truth". good law. home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny
1782951120 · [S5-B8 #3] search(Lynumn v. Illinois, 372 U.S. 528) x1 + search_document("must be deemed not voluntary") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Lynumn v. Illinois · opinion 106558 · 372 U.S. 528 (1963), No. 9, decided 1963-03-25 (Stewart, J.). HOLDING: confession coerced/involuntary where police threatened to cut off ADC aid and take suspect's children unless she cooperated; person w/ no criminal-law experience, no adviser, encircled by officers. quotes p.534 "the petitioner's oral confession was made only after the police had told her that state financial aid for her infant children would be cut off, and her children taken from her, if she did not 'cooperate.'...a confession made under such circumstances must be deemed not voluntary, but coerced...whether the defendant's will was overborne at the time he confessed"; p.534 "the confession cannot be deemed 'the product of a rational intellect and a free will'" (quoting Blackburn v. Alabama 361 U.S. 199, 208). good law. home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny
1782951480 · [S5-B8 #4] search(Beecher v. Alabama, 389 U.S. 35) x1 + search_document("product of gross coercion") x1 + read_document[chunk0] x1 · ok · Beecher v. Alabama · opinion 107526 · 389 U.S. 35 (1967), No. 92 Misc., decided 1967-10-23 (per curiam; Black, J. concurring on 5A grounds). HOLDING: confession at gunpoint from wounded suspect threatened w/ death + 2nd statement signed 5 days later while on morphine/in intense pain = product of gross coercion, involuntary; no conviction tainted by such confession can stand. quotes p.38 "this petitioner's confessions were the product of gross coercion. Under the Due Process Clause...no conviction tainted by a confession so obtained can stand"; p.38 "no break in the stream of events" (quoting Clewis v. Texas 386 U.S. 707, 710). good law (per curiam). NOTE: distinct from Beecher v. Alabama 408 U.S. 234 (1972) (Beecher II, retrial). home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny
1782951840 · [S5-B8 #5] search(Haynes v. Washington, 373 U.S. 503) x1 + search_document("atmosphere of substantial coercion and inducement") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · Haynes v. Washington · opinion 106625 · 373 U.S. 503 (1963), No. 147, decided 1963-05-27 (Goldberg, J.; 5-4). HOLDING: written confession obtained in atmosphere of substantial coercion/inducement — incommunicado detention + express threat of continued isolation + promise of contact w/ family conditioned on signing — is involuntary under totality, inadmissible (14A). quotes p.513 "the petitioner's written confession was obtained in an atmosphere of substantial coercion and inducement created by statements and actions of state authorities"; p.514 "Confronted with the express threat of continued incommunicado detention and induced by the promise of communication with and access to family, Haynes understandably chose to...sign...that choice cannot be said to be the voluntary product of a free and unconstrained will"; p.514-515 "the secret and incommunicado detention and interrogation—are devices adapted and used to extort confessions". cites Lynumn 372 U.S. 528, 534. good law. home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny
1782952200 · [S5-B8 #6] search(Townsend v. Sain, 372 U.S. 293) x1 + search_document("truth serum") x1 · ok · Townsend v. Sain · opinion 106544 · 372 U.S. 293 (1963), No. 8, decided 1963-03-18 (Warren, C.J.). HOLDING (homed): drug/'truth serum'-induced confession (hyoscine=scopolamine) not the product of a free intellect is involuntary/inadmissible regardless of who administered it or its reliability. quotes p.307-308 "If an individual's 'will was overborne' or if his confession was not 'the product of a rational intellect and a free will,' his confession is inadmissible because coerced...equally applicable to a drug-induced statement...Any questioning by police officers which in fact produces a confession which is not the product of a free intellect renders that confession inadmissible"; p.308 n.5 "whether scopolamine produces true confessions or false confessions, if it in fact caused Townsend to make statements, those statements were constitutionally inadmissible". TREATMENT/SR-5 FLAG: separate federal-habeas evidentiary-hearing holding (Townsend circumstances/deliberate-bypass) ABROGATED by Keeney v. Tamayo-Reyes 504 U.S. 1 (1992) + superseded by AEDPA §2254(e)(2); voluntariness holding remains good law (home-by-holding N1). home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny
1782952560 · [S5-B8 #7] search(Lego v. Twomey, 404 U.S. 477) x1 + search_document("preponderance of the evidence that the confession was voluntary") x1 · ok · Lego v. Twomey · opinion 108429 · 404 U.S. 477 (1972), No. 70-5037, decided 1972-01-12 (White, J.; Brennan/Douglas/Marshall dissent). HOLDING: prosecution need prove confession voluntariness only by a preponderance (not beyond reasonable doubt); defendant not entitled to have jury redetermine voluntariness after judge ruled; states may adopt higher standard. quote p.489 "he is entitled to a reliable and clear-cut determination that the confession was in fact voluntarily rendered. Thus, the prosecution must prove at least by a preponderance of the evidence that the confession was voluntary. Of course, the States are free, pursuant to their own law, to adopt a higher standard". good law (extended to Miranda waiver in Colorado v. Connelly). home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Progeny
1782952920 · [S5-B8 #8] search(Mallory v. United States, 354 U.S. 449) x1 + search_document("without unnecessary delay") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · Mallory v. United States · opinion 105545 · 354 U.S. 449 (1957), No. 521, decided 1957-06-24 (Frankfurter, J., unanimous). HOLDING: confession obtained during unnecessary presentment delay (Fed. R. Crim. P. 5(a)) inadmissible in federal prosecution; delay to extract a confession = unnecessary delay. quotes p.454 "he is not to be taken to police headquarters in order to carry out a process of inquiry that lends itself...to eliciting damaging statements"; p.455 "the command does not call for mechanical or automatic obedience...But the delay must not be of a nature to give opportunity for the extraction of a confession". Reversed and remanded. good law; federal Rule 5(a) rule; later modified (not supplanted) by §3501 six-hour safe harbor per Corley. home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Anchor
1782953280 · [S5-B8 #9] search(McNabb v. United States, 318 U.S. 332) x1 + search_document("duty of courts as agencies of justice") x1 + search_document("flagrant disregard of the procedure which Congress has commanded") x1 · ok · McNabb v. United States · opinion 103791 · 318 U.S. 332 (1943), No. 25, decided 1943-06-07 (Frankfurter, J.). HOLDING: under federal supervisory power (not Constitution), confessions obtained during prolonged detention in flagrant disregard of statutory prompt-presentment duty are inadmissible in federal court. quotes p.345 "a conviction resting on evidence secured through such a flagrant disregard of the procedure which Congress has commanded cannot be allowed to stand without making the courts themselves accomplices in wilful disobedience of law...would stultify the policy which Congress has enacted into law"; p.347 "a decent regard for the duty of courts as agencies of justice and custodians of liberty forbids that men should be convicted upon evidence secured under the circumstances revealed here...The history of liberty has largely been the history of observance of procedural safeguards". Reversed. good law; 'McNabb' half of McNabb-Mallory; federal supervisory/Rule 5(a) rule, modified not supplanted by §3501 per Corley. home=[[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Anchor
1782953640 · [S5-B8 #10] search(Florida v. Powell, 559 U.S. 50) x1 + search_document("not dictated the words") x1 + search_document("but at all times") x1 + read_document[chunk4,chunk5] x2 · ok · Florida v. Powell · opinion 1736 · 559 U.S. 50 (2010), No. 08-1175, decided 2010-02-23 (Ginsburg, J.; Stevens dissenting). HOLDING: Miranda warnings need not use precise words; 4 warnings substantively invariable but test is whether warnings reasonably convey suspect's rights; Tampa warnings ("right to talk to a lawyer before answering" + "use any of these rights at any time during this interview") adequately conveyed right to counsel during interrogation. quotes p.60 "The four warnings Miranda requires are invariable, but this Court has not dictated the words in which the essential information must be conveyed...The inquiry is simply whether the warnings reasonably 'conve[y] to [a suspect] his rights as required by Miranda'" (quoting Duckworth 492 U.S. 195, 203 / Prysock 453 U.S. 355, 361); p.62 "In combination, the two warnings reasonably conveyed Powell's right to have an attorney present, not only at the outset of interrogation, but at all times". good law. NOTE: Prysock/Duckworth named in italics (later-batch, no page yet). home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny
1782954000 · [S5-B8 #11] search(Arizona v. Mauro, 481 U.S. 520) x1 + search_document("interrogate a suspect simply by hoping") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · Arizona v. Mauro · opinion 111878 · 481 U.S. 520 (1987), No. 85-2121, decided 1987-06-26 (Powell, J.; Stevens dissenting 4). HOLDING: allowing a suspect who invoked Miranda to speak w/ his wife w/ an officer present + recorder running is NOT interrogation or its functional equivalent (Innis); officers don't interrogate by hoping suspect incriminates himself; volunteered statements admissible. quotes p.527-528 "Mauro was not interrogated...There is no evidence that the officers sent Mrs. Mauro in to see her husband for the purpose of eliciting incriminating statements"; p.529 "Officers do not interrogate a suspect simply by hoping that he will incriminate himself...Mauro was not subjected to compelling influences, psychological ploys, or direct questioning". good law. home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny (interrogation)
1782954360 · [S5-B8 #12] search(Pennsylvania v. Bruder, 488 U.S. 9) x1 + search_document("Berkemer") x1 · ok · Pennsylvania v. Bruder · opinion 112152 · 488 U.S. 9 (1988), No. 88-161, decided 1988-10-31 (per curiam; Marshall/Stevens dissent). HOLDING: ordinary roadside DUI questioning during a routine traffic stop is non-custodial; no Miranda warnings required before arrest; roadside responses admissible (applies Berkemer). quotes p.10 "persons temporarily detained pursuant to such stops are not 'in custody' for the purposes of Miranda" (quoting Berkemer 468 U.S. 420, 440); "he was not entitled to a recitation of his constitutional rights prior to arrest, and his roadside responses to questioning were admissible"; p.11 "Berkemer's rule, that ordinary traffic stops do not involve custody for purposes of Miranda, governs this case". cites California v. Beheler 463 U.S. 1121, 1125. good law. home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Related (custody)
1782954720 · [S5-B8 #13] search(Beckwith v. United States, 425 U.S. 341) x1 + search_document("compulsive aspect of custodial interrogation") x1 + read_document[chunk0,chunk1] x2 · ok · Beckwith v. United States · opinion 109430 · 425 U.S. 341 (1976), No. 74-1243, decided 1976-04-21 (Burger, C.J.; Brennan/Marshall dissent). HOLDING: Miranda triggered by custody, not investigative 'focus'; noncustodial IRS Intelligence Division interview of a criminal-tax target in a private home requires no Miranda warnings. quotes p.346 "it was the custodial nature of the interrogation which triggered the necessity for adherence to the specific requirements of its Miranda holding" (citing Orozco, Mathis); p.346-347 "It was the compulsive aspect of custodial interrogation, and not the strength or content of the government's suspicions...which led the court to impose the Miranda requirements" (quoting Caiello 420 F.2d 471, 473); p.347 focus = "questioning initiated...after a person has been taken into custody or otherwise deprived of his freedom of action in any significant way" (quoting Miranda 384 U.S. at 444). distinguishes Mathis (391 U.S. 1, IRS interview when in custody). good law. home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny (custody)
1782955080 · [S5-B8 #14] search(Mathis v. United States, 391 U.S. 1) x1 + search_document("entirely separate offense") x1 + read_document[chunk0] x1 · ok · Mathis v. United States (1968) · opinion 107676 · 391 U.S. 1 (1968), No. 726, decided 1968-05-06 (Black, J.; White/Harlan/Stewart dissent). HOLDING: Miranda required when a person already in custody (serving a prison sentence) is interrogated by a revenue agent, even though questioning concerns an entirely separate matter / routine tax investigation; reason for custody irrelevant. quotes p.4 "These differences are too minor and shadowy to justify a departure from the well-considered conclusions of Miranda with reference to warnings to be given to a person held in custody"; p.4-5 "There is no substance to such a distinction...We find nothing in the Miranda opinion which calls for a curtailment of the warnings...based on the reason why the person is in custody". YEAR-SUFFIX COLLISION: file 'Mathis v. United States (1968).md' (vs existing 'United States v. Mathis' 11th Cir 2014 + the famous 2016 sentencing 'Mathis v. United States'); alias bare 'Mathis v. United States'. N4/SR-5 FLAG: treatment=limited by Howes v. Fields 565 U.S. 499 (2012) (incarceration alone != automatic Miranda custody; totality test). home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny (custody)
1782955440 · [S5-B8 #15] search(California v. Beheler, 463 U.S. 1121) x1 + search_document("degree associated with a formal arrest") x1 + read_document[chunk0,chunk1] x2 · ok · California v. Beheler · opinion 111023 · 463 U.S. 1121 (1983), No. 82-1666, decided 1983-07-06 (per curiam; Stevens/Brennan/Marshall dissent). HOLDING: suspect not under arrest who voluntarily comes to station & is allowed to leave after brief interview is NOT in Miranda custody; ultimate test = formal arrest or restraint on freedom of movement 'of the degree associated with a formal arrest'. quotes p.1123 "Beheler was neither taken into custody nor significantly deprived of his freedom of action. Indeed, Beheler's freedom was not restricted in any way whatsoever"; p.1125 "the ultimate inquiry is simply whether there is a 'formal arrest or restraint on freedom of movement' of the degree associated with a formal arrest" (quoting Mathiason 429 U.S. 492, 495); "not required 'simply because the questioning takes place in the station house, or because the questioned person is one whom the police suspect'". good law. home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny (custody)
1782955800 · [S5-B8 #16] search(Thompson v. Keohane, 516 U.S. 99) x1 + search_document("at liberty to terminate the interrogation and leave") x1 + read_document[chunk3] x1 · ok · Thompson v. Keohane · opinion 117982 · 516 U.S. 99 (1995), No. 94-6615, decided 1995-11-29 (Ginsburg, J.; Thomas/Rehnquist dissent). HOLDING: Miranda custody = objective two-inquiry test (circumstances of interrogation [factual] + whether reasonable person would feel free to terminate & leave [objective]); ultimate custody determination is a mixed question of law and fact qualifying for independent federal habeas review (not §2254(d) presumption). quotes p.112 "Two discrete inquiries are essential...first, what were the circumstances...and second...would a reasonable person have felt he or she was not at liberty to terminate the interrogation and leave...objective test to resolve 'the ultimate inquiry': '[was] there a "formal arrest or restraint on freedom of movement" of the degree associated with a formal arrest'" (quoting Beheler 463 U.S. 1121, 1125); p.112-113 "This ultimate determination, we hold, presents a 'mixed question of law and fact' qualifying for independent review". good law (note: §2254(d) framework later changed by AEDPA; see Yarborough v. Alvarado). home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny (custody)
1782956160 · [S5-B8 #17] search(Yarborough v. Alvarado, 541 U.S. 652) x1 + search_document("have not mentioned the suspect's age") x1 + search_document("subjective inquiry") x1 + read_document[chunk4] x1 · ok · Yarborough v. Alvarado · opinion 134748 · 541 U.S. 652 (2004), No. 02-1684, decided 2004-06-01 (Kennedy, J.; O'Connor concur; Breyer/Stevens/Souter/Ginsburg dissent). HOLDING: under AEDPA, state court's finding that a 17-yr-old was not in custody was not an unreasonable application of clearly established law; Miranda custody test is objective and Court's cases had not made age/experience part of it. quotes p.665-666 "We cannot grant relief under AEDPA by conducting our own independent inquiry...Relief is available under §2254(d)(1) only if the state court's decision is objectively unreasonable"; p.666 "Our opinions applying the Miranda custody test have not mentioned the suspect's age, much less mandated its consideration"; p.668 "the custody inquiry states an objective rule designed to give clear guidance to the police, while consideration of a suspect's individual characteristics—including his age—could be viewed as creating a subjective inquiry". N4/SR-5 FLAG: qualified for juveniles by J.D.B. v. North Carolina 564 U.S. 261 (2011) (child's age part of custody analysis when known/objectively apparent; J.D.B. distinguished Alvarado as AEDPA holding). good law. home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny (custody)
1782956520 · [S5-B8 #18] search(Pennsylvania v. Muniz, 496 U.S. 582) x1 + search_document("routine booking question") x1 + search_document("incriminating...answer's content") x1[no-match] + search_document("physical manner in which he articulates words") x1 + read_document[chunk4] x1 · ok · Pennsylvania v. Muniz · opinion 112464 · 496 U.S. 582 (1990), No. 89-213, decided 1990-06-18 (Brennan, J.; fractured/plurality on parts). HOLDINGS: (1) slurred speech/lack of muscular coordination = non-testimonial physical evidence (admissible w/o Miranda); (2) 'sixth birthday' answer = testimonial (content reveals impaired mental state; custodial+unwarned -> suppress); (3) 7 biographical booking questions within 'routine booking question' exception to Miranda. quotes p.590-591 "any slurring of speech...constitute nontestimonial components...Requiring a suspect to reveal the physical manner in which he articulates words...does not, without more, compel him to provide a 'testimonial' response"; p.599 "the incriminating inference of impaired mental faculties stemmed, not just from the fact that Muniz slurred his response, but also from a testimonial aspect of that response"; p.600 "Muniz's response to the sixth birthday question was testimonial, the response should have been suppressed"; p.601 "a 'routine booking question' exception which exempts from Miranda's coverage questions to secure the 'biographical data necessary to complete booking or pretrial services'". good law (fractured). home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Progeny
1783000000 · [S5-B9 #1] search(California v. Prysock, citation 451 U.S. 355) x1[0-results] + search(q="California v. Prysock Miranda warnings") x1 + search_document(110556,"talismanic incantation") x1 + read_document[chunk1] x1 · ok · California v. Prysock · opinion 110556 (merits per curiam; NOT the 110503 in-chambers stay) · 451 U.S. 355 (1981), No. 80-1846, decided 1981-06-23 (per curiam; Stevens/Brennan/Marshall dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (juvenile murder suspect; appointed-counsel warning adequacy). HOLDING: Miranda warnings need not be a verbatim recital; reasonably-conveys standard. quotes *359 "This Court has never indicated that the 'rigidity' of Miranda extends to the precise formulation of the warnings given a criminal defendant"; *359 "Miranda itself indicated that no talismanic incantation was required to satisfy its strictures"; *359 "a verbatim recital of the words of the Miranda opinion" (not required). star *360 CONFIRMED via chunk1. good law (reaffirmed Duckworth 1989, Florida v. Powell 2010). home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Key—Progeny (warning adequacy). Queue role Related→Key (N6: central to warning-adequacy doctrine).
1783000300 · [S5-B9 #2] search(q="Duckworth v. Eagan if and when you go to court Miranda") x1 + search_document(112322,"as if construing a will") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · Duckworth v. Eagan · opinion 112322 · 492 U.S. 195 (1989), No. 88-317, decided 1989-06-26 (Rehnquist, C.J.; O'Connor concur; Marshall dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Indiana stabbing; "if and when you go to court" warning). HOLDING: warnings need not be verbatim; reasonably-conveys test; "if and when" language adequate in totality. quotes *203 "Reviewing courts therefore need not examine Miranda warnings as if construing a will or defining the terms of an easement. The inquiry is simply whether the warnings reasonably 'conve[y] to [a suspect] his rights as required by Miranda.'"; *204 Miranda "does not require that attorneys be producible on call"; *205 "We hold that the initial warnings given to respondent, in their totality, satisfied Miranda". star *204/*205 CONFIRMED via chunk2. good law (applies Prysock; reaffirmed Florida v. Powell 2010). home=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Key—Progeny (warning adequacy).
1783000600 · [S5-B9 #3] search(q="Chavez v. Martinez self-incrimination coercive questioning Section 1983") x1 + search_document(127927,"We fail to see how, based on the text of the Fifth Amendment") x1 + read_document[chunk2] x1 · ok · Chavez v. Martinez · opinion 127927 (538 U.S. 760; NOT 127891 "538 U.S. 1" stray cite) · 538 U.S. 760 (2003), No. 01-1444, decided 2003-05-27 (Thomas plurality announcing judgment; Souter+Breyer controlling rationale/remand; fractured). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Oxnard shooting; coercive hospital interrogation; § 1983). HOLDING: Self-Incrimination Clause is a trial right; no completed 5A violation absent use of statement in a criminal case -> no § 1983 5A claim; substantive-DP claim remanded. quotes (plurality) "We fail to see how, based on the text of the Fifth Amendment, Martinez can allege a violation of this right, since Martinez was never prosecuted for a crime, let alone compelled to be a witness against himself in a criminal case"; "it is not until their use in a criminal case that a violation of the Self-Incrimination Clause occurs" (Verdugo-Urquidez "fundamental trial right"). CAVEAT (L1): CL record 127927 renders star-pagination as malformed "* N" markers (not clean U.S.-Reports stars); verbatim quotes CONFIRMED via search_document+chunk2; pinpoints 766-767 assigned from the canonical 538 U.S. citation. good law (carried forward by Vega v. Tekoh 2022). homes=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[Due-Process Voluntariness of Confessions]] Related.
1783000900 · [S5-B9 #4] search(q="Vega v. Tekoh Miranda violation Section 1983") x1 + read_document(6480695 full)[WRONG-OPINION: cluster-id 6480695 resolves to an AZ Industrial-Commission opinion - L3 trap] + get_endpoint_item(clusters,6480695) x1 [-> sub_opinion 6352828] + search_document(6352828,"...does not necessarily constitute...")x1[0] + search_document(6352828,"we see no justification...")x1[0, newline-broke literal match] + search_document(6352828,"Tekoh")x1 + search_document(6352828,"is reversed")x1 · ok · Vega v. Tekoh · LEAD opinion 6352828 (cluster 6480695) · 597 U.S. 134 (2022), No. 21-499, argued 2022-04-20, decided 2022-06-23 (Alito, J., joined Roberts/Thomas/Gorsuch/Kavanaugh/Barrett; Kagan dissent joined Breyer/Sotomayor). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (LA Sheriff Dep. Carlos Vega; un-Mirandized statement; acquittal then § 1983). HOLDING (syllabus, verbatim): "A violation of the Miranda rules does not provide a basis for a §1983 claim." Conclusion (Alito, verbatim): "Because a violation of Miranda is not itself a violation of the Fifth Amendment, and because we see no justification for expanding Miranda to confer a right to sue under §1983, the judgment of the Court of Appeals is reversed". CAVEAT (L1): CL stores the SLIP opinion ("Cite as: 597 U. S. ____ (2022)") - no internal U.S.-Reports star pages; pin-134 = case start/Held (from cluster citation 597 U.S. 134); conclusion cited to the opinion, NO fabricated internal page (earlier ^pin-152 removed). good law (2022). homes=[[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny.
1783001200 · [S5-B9 #5] search(q="Doyle v. Ohio post-Miranda silence impeachment due process") x1 + search_document(109491,"silence will carry no penalty") x1 · ok · Doyle v. Ohio · opinion 109491 · 426 U.S. 610 (1976), No. 75-5014, decided 1976-06-17 (Powell, J.; Stevens/Blackmun/Rehnquist dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (marijuana sale; post-arrest silence used to impeach exculpatory trial story). HOLDING: impeachment use of post-arrest/post-Miranda silence violates Fourteenth Amendment Due Process. quotes *617 post-arrest silence "insolubly ambiguous"; *618 "while it is true that the Miranda warnings contain no express assurance that silence will carry no penalty, such assurance is implicit to any person who receives the warnings. In such circumstances, it would be fundamentally unfair and a deprivation of due process to allow the arrested person's silence to be used to impeach an explanation subsequently offered at trial." star *618/*619 CONFIRMED. good law (cabined by Jenkins v. Anderson / Fletcher v. Weir / Salinas to post-Miranda silence only). home=[[Miranda Waiver and Invocation]] Key—Progeny.
