1783003000 · [S5-B9 #11] search(q="Michigan v. Tucker Miranda prophylactic witness fruits voluntary", citation 417 U.S. 433) x1 + search_document(109063,"departed only from the prophylactic standards") x1 · ok · Michigan v. Tucker · opinion 109063 · 417 U.S. 433 (1974), No. 73-482, decided 1974-06-10 (Rehnquist, J.; White/Brennan/Marshall concur in judgment; Douglas dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (pre-Miranda rape interrogation, incomplete appointed-counsel warning; witness Henderson). HOLDING: fruits of a mere prophylactic Miranda violation (voluntary statement) need not be suppressed. quote *446 "the police conduct at issue here did not abridge respondent's constitutional privilege against compulsory self-incrimination, but departed only from the prophylactic standards later laid down by this Court in Miranda to safeguard that privilege" (Douglas dissent quotes same at *462-463). star *446 CONFIRMED. good law (Dickerson 2000 reaffirmed Miranda's constitutional status but Tucker fruits principle survives -> applied in Patane 2004). home=[[Miranda Waiver and Invocation]] Key—Progeny.
