1783005000 · [S5-B9 #17] search(q="Escobedo v. Illinois denied consult retained counsel interrogation Sixth Amendment", citation 378 U.S. 478) x1 + search_document(106883,"no longer a general inquiry into an unsolved crime but has begun to focus") x1 · ok · Escobedo v. Illinois · opinion 106883 · 378 U.S. 478 (1964), No. 615, decided 1964-06-22 (Goldberg, J.; Harlan/Stewart/White+Clark dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (murder of brother-in-law; denied access to retained lawyer at station; no silence warning). HOLDING: 6A right to counsel denied during focused custodial interrogation; statements inadmissible. quote *490-491 "We hold, therefore, that where, as here, the investigation is no longer a general inquiry into an unsolved crime but has begun to focus on a particular suspect, the suspect has been taken into police custody, the police carry out a process of interrogations that lends itself to eliciting incriminating statements, the suspect has requested and been denied an opportunity to consult with his lawyer, and the police have not effectively warned him of his absolute constitutional right to remain silent, the accused has been denied 'the Assistance of Counsel' in violation of the Sixth Amendment..." star *491 CONFIRMED. TREATMENT=limited (result intact; rationale recast as 5A by Miranda 1966, confined to its facts by Kirby v. Illinois 1972 / Moran v. Burbine 1986; SR-5/N13). authority_weight Binding—SCOTUS + treatment limited (orthogonal axes). homes=[[Sixth Amendment Right to Counsel]] Key—Historical + [[Miranda and Custodial Interrogation]] Related.
1783005400 · [S5-B9 #18] search(q="Foster v. California lineup suggestive due process identification all but inevitable", citation 394 U.S. 440) x1 + search_document(107890,"made it all but inevitable") x1 + read_document[chunk0] x1 · ok · Foster v. California · opinion 107890 · 394 U.S. 440 (1969), No. 47, argued 1968-11-19, decided 1969-04-01 (Fortas, J.; Black/Harlan/Stewart/White dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Western Union robbery; tall suspect + leather jacket; showup; repeat lineup). HOLDING: identification procedure so unnecessarily suggestive as to violate due process (rare DP reversal). quotes *442 "the conduct of identification procedures may be 'so unnecessarily suggestive and conducive to irreparable mistaken identification' as to be a denial of due process of law"; *443 "The suggestive elements in this identification procedure made it all but inevitable that David would identify petitioner whether or not he was in fact 'the man.' In effect, the police repeatedly said to the witness, 'This is the man.' ... This procedure so undermined the reliability of the eyewitness identification as to violate due process." star *441/*442/*443 CONFIRMED via chunk0. good law (cited as the rare such reversal in Perry v. New Hampshire 2012). home=[[Eyewitness Identification]] Key—Progeny.
1783100100 · [S5-B10 #1] search(type=o, q="Pembaur City of Cincinnati municipal liability single decision policymaker", citation 475 U.S. 469) x1 + search_document(111615,"a deliberate choice to follow a course of action is made from among various alternatives") x1 · ok · Pembaur v. City of Cincinnati · opinion 111615 (cluster 111615) · 475 U.S. 469 (1986), No. 84-1160, decided 1986-03-25 (Brennan, J.; plurality on single-decision point; White concur; Stevens concur; Powell+Burger+Rehnquist dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Dr. Pembaur clinic; deputies axe door to serve capiases on grand-jury witnesses; County Prosecutor told them "go in and get" them). HOLDING: a single decision by an official with FINAL POLICYMAKING AUTHORITY for the subject can be Monell "official policy." quote *483-484 "We hold that municipal liability under §1983 attaches where — and only where — a deliberate choice to follow a course of action is made from among various alternatives by the official or officials responsible for establishing final policy with respect to the subject matter in question." star *484 marker confirmed; O'Connor concurrence cross-refs "Ante, at 483-484." good law. home=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny/Refinement.
1783100500 · [S5-B10 #2] search(type=o, q="Messerschmidt Millender QI overbroad warrant magistrate", citation 565 U.S. 535) x1 + search_document(623242,"the fact that a neutral magistrate...")x1[0, 623242=combined doc] + search_document(623242,"threshold...high one")x1[0] + get_endpoint_item(clusters,623242)[sub_opinions->9485385 lead] + search_document(9485385,"threshold for establishing this exception is a high one")x1[1] + read_document(9485385,chunk2) x1 · ok · Messerschmidt v. Millender · LEAD opinion 9485385 (cluster 623242; canonical URL /opinion/623242/) · 565 U.S. 535 (2012), No. 10-704, decided 2012-02-22 (Roberts, C.J.; Breyer concur; Kagan concur/dissent; Sotomayor+Ginsburg dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Det. Messerschmidt; Jerry Bowen "black sawed-off shotgun with a pistol grip" assault on Shelly Kelly; warrant for ALL firearms + gang material at Augusta Millender's home; supervisor+DDA+magistrate approved). HOLDING: QI for obtaining/executing facially-overbroad magistrate-approved warrant; Malley exception is a HIGH threshold. quotes *547 "Nonetheless, under our precedents, the fact that a neutral magistrate has issued a warrant authorizing the allegedly unconstitutional search or seizure does not end the inquiry into objective reasonableness." + *547 Malley/Leon "so lacking in indicia of probable cause as to render official belief in its existence entirely unreasonable" (Leon 468 U.S. at 923) + *547 "Our precedents make clear, however, that the threshold for establishing this exception is a high one, and it should be." star *546/*547/*548 CONFIRMED via chunk2. good law. homes=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related.
1783100900 · [S5-B10 #3] search(type=o, q="Wilson v. Layne media ride-along home warrant QI", citation 526 U.S. 603) x1 + search_document(118289,"bring members of the media or other third parties into a home during the execution of a warrant")x1[1] + search_document(118289,"it was not unreasonable for a police officer in April 1992 to have believed")x1[1] + read_document(118289,chunk3) x1 · ok · Wilson v. Layne · opinion 118289 (cluster 118289) · 526 U.S. 603 (1999), No. 98-83, decided 1999-05-24 (Rehnquist, C.J., unanimous on 4A; Stevens concur/dissent on QI). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (1992 Marshals + county police; Washington Post reporter+photographer into Charles & Geraldine Wilson home executing arrest warrant for son Dominic; Bivens/§1983). HOLDINGS: (1) media into home during warrant execution not in aid of warrant violates 4A; (2) QI - right not clearly established in 1992. quotes *614 "We hold that it is a violation of the Fourth Amendment for police to bring members of the media or other third parties into a home during the execution of a warrant when the presence of the third parties in the home was not in aid of the execution of the warrant." + *615 "We hold that it was not unreasonable for a police officer in April 1992 to have believed that bringing media observers along during the execution of an arrest warrant (even in a home) was lawful." star *614/*615/*616/*617 CONFIRMED via chunk3 (cites Anderson v. Creighton, Harlow). good law. homes=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related. Companion=[[Hanlon v. Berger]].
1783101300 · [S5-B10 #4] search(type=o, citation 526 U.S. 808)x1[0] + search(case_name="Hanlon v. Berger")x1[->SCOTUS cluster 1087699] + search_document(1087699,"Wilson v. Layne")x1[0, syllabus-stored] + read_document(1087699 full, 5369 chars) x1 · ok · Hanlon v. Berger · opinion 1087699 (cluster 1087699) · 526 U.S. 808 (1999), No. 97-1927, argued 1999-03-24, decided 1999-05-24 (per curiam; Stevens concur/dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Paul & Erma Berger 75,000-acre ranch near Jordan MT; warrant for unlawful taking of wildlife excluding residence; CNN crew accompanied US Fish & Wildlife agents; Bivens suit). HOLDING: 4A violation under Wilson v. Layne; QI applies (right not clearly established in 1992/1993). quotes *810 "Review of the complaint's much more detailed allegations to the same effect satisfies us that respondents alleged a Fourth Amendment violation under our decision today in Wilson v. Layne, ante, p. 603." + *810 "Petitioners maintain that even though they may have violated the Fourth Amendment rights of respondents, they are entitled to the defense of qualified immunity. We agree. Our holding in Wilson makes clear that this right was not clearly established in 1992." star *809/*810 CONFIRMED via full read. good law. home=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny (queue-hint "Related"; companion to Wilson). Companion=[[Wilson v. Layne]]; Bivens=[[Bivens v. Six Unknown Named Agents]].
1783101700 · [S5-B10 #5] search_document(111611,"a reasonably well-trained officer in petitioner's position would have known that his affidavit failed to establish probable cause")x1[1] + search_document(111611,"no reasonably competent officer would have concluded that a warrant should issue")x1[3] · ok · Malley v. Briggs · opinion 111611 (cluster 111611; URL /opinion/111611/) · 475 U.S. 335 (1986), No. 84-1586, decided 1986-03-05 (White, J.; Powell concur/dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (RI trooper Malley; wiretap-based felony complaints + affidavits v. James & Louise Briggs; grand jury no-billed; §1983). HOLDING: warrant-applying officer gets QUALIFIED not absolute immunity; lost where no reasonably competent officer would have sought the warrant. quotes *341 "Defendants will not be immune if, on an objective basis, it is obvious that no reasonably competent officer would have concluded that a warrant should issue; but if officers of reasonable competence could disagree on this issue, immunity should be recognized." + *341 "all but the plainly incompetent or those who knowingly violate the law" + *345 "The analogous question in this case is whether a reasonably well-trained officer in petitioner's position would have known that his affidavit failed to establish probable cause and that he should not have applied for the warrant." star *341 (dissent cross-ref "Ante, at 341") + *350 confirmed. good law. homes=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related.
1783102100 · [S5-B10 #6] search(type=o, q="City of Canton v. Harris failure to train deliberate indifference", citation 489 U.S. 378) x1 + search_document(112209,"the failure to train amounts to deliberate indifference to the rights of persons")x1[1] + search_document(112209,"the need for more or different training is so obvious")x1[2] · ok · City of Canton v. Harris · opinion 112209 (cluster 112209) · 489 U.S. 378 (1989), No. 86-1088, decided 1989-02-28 (White, J.; Brennan concur; O'Connor concur/dissent w/ Scalia+Kennedy). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Geraldine Harris; Canton OH stationhouse; slumped to floor, no medical care summoned; §1983 failure-to-train re: medical care for detainees). HOLDING: municipal failure-to-train liability ONLY on deliberate indifference. quotes *388 "We hold today that the inadequacy of police training may serve as the basis for §1983 liability only where the failure to train amounts to deliberate indifference to the rights of persons with whom the police come into contact." (star *389 immediately after) + *390 "the need for more or different training is so obvious, and the inadequacy so likely to result in the violation of constitutional rights, that the policymakers of the city can reasonably be said to have been deliberately indifferent to the need." (O'Connor cross-ref "Ante, at 390"). good law. home=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny (Monell line).
1783102600 · [S5-B10 #7] search(type=o, q="Connick v. Thompson single Brady violation failure to train", citation 563 U.S. 51) x1 + search_document(213505,"A pattern of similar constitutional violations...")x1[0,combined doc 167k] + search_document(213505,"ordinarily necessary...")x1[0] + search_document(9441299,"ordinarily necessary")x1[4] + read_document(9441299,chunk3) x1 · ok · Connick v. Thompson · LEAD opinion 9441299 (cluster 213505; canonical URL /opinion/213505/) · 563 U.S. 51 (2011), No. 09-571, decided 2011-03-29 (Thomas, J., 5-4; Scalia concur; Ginsburg dissent w/ Breyer/Sotomayor/Kagan). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (John Thompson; New Orleans DA Harry Connick; suppressed crime-lab/blood report; armed-robbery+murder; $14M jury verdict). HOLDING: single Brady violation w/o pattern insufficient for failure-to-train deliberate indifference. quotes *62 "A pattern of similar constitutional violations by untrained employees is 'ordinarily necessary' to demonstrate deliberate indifference for purposes of failure to train." (Bryan Cty. 520 U.S. at 409) + *64 "Failure to train prosecutors in their Brady obligations does not fall within the narrow range of Canton's hypothesized single-incident liability." star *62/*63/*64 CONFIRMED via chunk3 (cites Pembaur, Canton, Brady). good law. homes=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[Brady and Giglio]] Related.
