1783103600 · [S5-B10 #9] search(type=o, q="United States v. Classic misuse of power under color of state law", citation 313 U.S. 299) x1 + search_document(103531,"Misuse of power, possessed by virtue of state law and made possible only because the wrongdoer is clothed with the authority of state law")x1[1] + read_document(103531,chunk8) x1 · ok · United States v. Classic · opinion 103531 (cluster 103531) · 313 U.S. 299 (1941), No. 618, decided 1941-05-26 (Stone, J.; Douglas+Black+Murphy concur/dissent in part). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Louisiana election commissioners; §§19/20 Criminal Code now 18 USC 241/242; altered/falsely counted Democratic primary ballots for US House). HOLDING: misuse of state-conferred power = "under color of" state law (color-of-law anchor); right to vote in integral primary is constitutionally protected. quote (para 30) "Misuse of power, possessed by virtue of state law and made possible only because the wrongdoer is clothed with the authority of state law, is action taken 'under color of' state law." (Ex parte Virginia 100 U.S. 339, 346). PAGINATION: CL stores paragraph-numbered format (no star *326 markers in chunk8); pin 326 per official U.S. Reports citation (the universally-cited page for this sentence). good law (definition carried into Screws + adopted for §1983 in Monroe v. Pape; Classic overruled Grovey v. Townsend on primary point). home=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Anchor (color of law).
