1783104700 · [S5-B10 #11] search(type=o, q="Ashcroft v. al-Kidd material witness pretext objective", citation 563 U.S. 731) x1[2 clusters: 217703 + 7344719] + search_document(7262676,"whether the circumstances viewed objectively...")x1[0] + search_document(217703,"predominantly an objective inquiry")x1[1,syllabus] + search_document(217703,"whatever the subjective intent...")x1[0,line-breaks] + read_document(217703,[2,3]) + read_document(217703,chunk5) · ok · Ashcroft v. al-Kidd · opinion 217703 (also cluster 7344719/lead 7262676; used /opinion/217703/ which resolves + shows named case) · 563 U.S. 731 (2011), No. 10-98, decided 2011-05-31 (Scalia, J.; Kennedy concur; Ginsburg + Sotomayor concur in judgment; Kagan took no part). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (John D. Ashcroft v. Abdullah al-Kidd; 2003 material-witness warrant; Bivens; alleged AG pretext policy; 9th Cir.). HOLDINGS: (1) subjective intent irrelevant to 4A objective reasonableness; (2) Ashcroft did not violate clearly established law -> QI. quotes (slip op. 3-4, U.S. 736) "Fourth Amendment reasonableness 'is predominantly an objective inquiry.' We ask whether 'the circumstances, viewed objectively, justify [the challenged] action.' If so, that action was reasonable 'whatever the subjective intent' motivating the relevant officials." (Edmond/Scott/Whren) + (slip op. 12, U.S. 743) "We hold that an objectively reasonable arrest and detention of a material witness pursuant to a validly obtained warrant cannot be challenged as unconstitutional on the basis of allegations that the arresting authority had an improper motive." + (743) QI "protects 'all but the plainly incompetent or those who knowingly violate the law.'" (Malley 475 U.S. 341). PAGINATION: slip "563 U. S. ____ (2011)"; pins keyed to official U.S. Reports 736/743 (743 confirmed via Messerschmidt cross-cite "563 U.S. 731, 743"). good law. homes=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[Seizure of the Person]] Related.
1783105300 · [S5-B10 #12] search(type=o, q="White v. Pauly QI clearly established officer arrived late deadly force per curiam") x1 + search_document(4151832,"do not by themselves create clearly established law outside an obvious case")x1[0,line-breaks] + read_document(4151832,[1,2]) · ok · White v. Pauly · opinion 4151832 (cluster 4374579; canonical URL /opinion/4374579/) · 580 U.S. 73 (2017), No. 16-67, decided 2017-01-09 (per curiam; Ginsburg concurring). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Ray White et al. v. Daniel T. Pauly, est. of Samuel Pauly; NM State Police Truesdale/Mariscal/White; reckless-driving report; Paulys armed "We have guns"; White arrived late, shot Samuel w/o warning; §1983 excessive force; 10th Cir. denied QI). HOLDING: clearly established law must be particularized; Garner/Graham alone don't clearly establish outside an obvious case; late-arriving officer gets QI. quotes (slip op. 6) "it is again necessary to reiterate the longstanding principle that 'clearly established law' should not be defined 'at a high level of generality' ... the clearly established law must be 'particularized' to the facts of the case." (al-Kidd 563 U.S. 742; Anderson v. Creighton 483 U.S. 640) + (slip op. 6) "The panel majority misunderstood the 'clearly established' analysis: It failed to identify a case where an officer acting under similar circumstances as Officer White was held to have violated the Fourth Amendment." + (slip op. 7) "we have held that Garner and Graham do not by themselves create clearly established law outside 'an obvious case.'" (Brosseau 543 U.S. 199). PAGINATION: slip "580 U. S. ____ (2017)"; pins keyed to official case-start 73, slip op. 6-7 (verifiable). good law. homes=[[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Key—Progeny + [[Use of Force]] Related.
