1783106500 · [S5-B10 #14] search(type=o, q="Plumhoff v. Rickard deadly force high-speed chase QI fifteen shots", citation 572 U.S. 765) x1 + search_document(2675750,"the officers need not stop shooting until the threat has ended")x1[1] + read_document(2675750,chunk5) + read_document(2675750,chunk6) · ok · Plumhoff v. Rickard · opinion 2675750 (cluster 2675750) · 572 U.S. 765 (2014), No. 12-1117, decided 2014-05-27 (Alito, J., unanimous). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Officer Vance Plumhoff et al. v. Whitne Rickard, admin. of Donald Rickard; West Memphis AR; broken-headlight stop -> 100+ mph 5-min chase; Rickard + passenger Kelly Allen killed by 15 shots). HOLDINGS: (1) deadly force to end dangerous chase reasonable; 15 shots not excessive; (2) alternatively QI. quotes *777 "it is beyond serious dispute that Rickard's flight posed a grave public safety risk, and here, as in Scott, the police acted reasonably in using deadly force to end that risk." + *777 "It stands to reason that, if police officers are justified in firing at a suspect in order to end a severe threat to public safety, the officers need not stop shooting until the threat has ended." + *778 "We have held that petitioners' conduct did not violate the Fourth Amendment, but even if that were not the case, petitioners would still be entitled to summary judgment based on qualified immunity." page-labels *776/*777/*778/*779 CONFIRMED (CL uses proper page-label markup; cites Scott v. Harris, al-Kidd, Brosseau, Garner/Graham). good law (totality analysis consistent w/ Barnes v. Felix 2025). homes=[[Use of Force]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related.
1783107200 · [S5-B10 #15] search(type=o, q="San Francisco v. Sheehan QI mentally ill knife second entry ADA", citation 575 U.S. 600) x1 + search_document(2801435,"did not violate clearly established law")x1[0] + search_document(2801435,"qualified immunity because they did not violate any clearly established")x1[1] + read_document(2801435,chunk7) · ok · City and County of San Francisco v. Sheehan · opinion 2801435 (cluster 2801435) · 575 U.S. 600 (2015), No. 13-1412, decided 2015-05-18 (Alito, J.; Scalia+Kagan concur/dissent in part; Breyer recused). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Teresa Sheehan schizoaffective, SF group home; Sgt. Kimberly Reynolds + Officer Kathrine Holder; knife threat; second entry; pepper spray + shots, survived; ADA + §1983). HOLDINGS: (1) ADA question DISMISSED as improvidently granted; (2) officers entitled to QI - no clearly established 4A violation. quotes (opening, U.S. 600) "we dismiss the first question as improvidently granted. We decide the second question and hold that the officers are entitled to qualified immunity because they did not violate any clearly established Fourth Amendment rights." + (p-52) "no precedent clearly established that there was not 'an objective need for immediate entry' here ... Without that 'fair notice,' an officer is entitled to qualified immunity." + (p-56, 135 S.Ct. 1778) "In sum, we hold that qualified immunity applies because these officers had no 'fair and clear warning of what the Constitution requires.'" PAGINATION: CL page-labels mix U.S.Reports + S.Ct.; pinned 600 (U.S. opening) + 135 S.Ct. 1778 (parallel, page-label confirmed after *1778 marker). good law. homes=[[Use of Force]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related.
1783107800 · [S5-B10 #16] search(type=o, q="Kingsley v. Hendrickson pretrial detainee excessive force objective reasonableness", citation 576 U.S. 389) x1 + search_document(2811847,"a pretrial detainee must show only...")x1[0] + search_document(2811847,"purposely or knowingly used against him was objectively unreasonable")x1[0] + search_document(9808641,"objectively unreasonable")x1[6] · ok · Kingsley v. Hendrickson · LEAD opinion 9808641 (cluster 2811847; canonical URL /opinion/2811847/) · 576 U.S. 389 (2015), No. 14-6368, decided 2015-06-22 (Breyer, J., 5-4; Scalia dissent w/ Roberts/Thomas; Alito dissent). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Michael Kingsley v. Stan Hendrickson; WI jail pretrial detainee; refused to remove paper over light; head slammed on bunk + Taser; §1983 14A excessive force; jury given subjective "reckless" instruction). HOLDING: pretrial-detainee 14A excessive force = OBJECTIVE reasonableness only. quote (*2473 / U.S. 396-397) "we agree with the dissenting appeals court judge, the Seventh Circuit's jury instruction committee, and Kingsley, that a pretrial detainee must show only that the force purposely or knowingly used against him was objectively unreasonable." page-label *2473 confirmed (dissent cross-ref "Ante, at 2473"); pin U.S. 396-397 (135 S.Ct. 2473). good law. homes=[[Use of Force]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related.
1783108500 · [S5-B10 #17] [QUEUE-FLAGGED RECENT 2025 - identity confirmed] search(type=o, q="Barnes v. Felix excessive force totality moment of threat") x1 + search_document(11051434,"totality of the circumstances moment of the threat")x1[0,slip line-breaks] + read_document(11051434,[0,1]) + read_document(11051434,chunk3) · ok · Barnes v. Felix · opinion 11051434 (cluster 10584846; also dup cluster 10776852) · 605 U.S. 73 (2025), No. 23-1239, argued 2025-01-22, decided 2025-05-15 (Kagan, J., UNANIMOUS; Kavanaugh concur w/ Thomas/Alito/Barrett). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Janice Hughes Barnes, est. of Ashtian Barnes; Officer Roberto Felix Jr.; Houston toll-violation stop; Felix jumped on doorsill of moving Corolla, 2 shots; §1983; 5th Cir. "moment-of-threat" rule). HOLDING: 4A excessive-force reasonableness = totality of circumstances, NO time limit; moment-of-threat rule rejected. quotes (slip op. 1) "Today, we reject that approach as improperly narrowing the requisite Fourth Amendment analysis. To assess whether an officer acted reasonably in using force, a court must consider all the relevant circumstances, including facts and events leading up to the climactic moment." + (slip op. 7) "A court deciding a use-of-force case cannot review the totality of the circumstances if it has put on chronological blinders." PAGINATION: slip "605 U. S. ____ (2025)" subject to formal revision; pins keyed to official case-start 73, slip op. 1/7. GOOD LAW (2025, unanimous; confirms Plumhoff totality; abrogates 5th Cir. moment-of-threat; left open QI + officer-created-danger). homes=[[Use of Force]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related.
1783109100 · [S5-B10 #18] search(type=o, q="County of Sacramento v. Lewis high-speed pursuit substantive due process shocks the conscience", citation 523 U.S. 833) x1 + search_document(118214,"only a purpose to cause harm unrelated to the legitimate object of arrest...")x1[1] + search_document(118214,"high-speed chases with no intent to harm suspects physically or to worsen their legal plight")x1[1] · ok · County of Sacramento v. Lewis · opinion 118214 (cluster 118214) · 523 U.S. 833 (1998), No. 96-1337, decided 1998-05-26 (Souter, J.; multiple concurrences - Rehnquist, Kennedy+O'Connor, Breyer, Stevens, Scalia+Thomas). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Sacramento County deputies James Everett Smith + Murray Stapp; motorcycle Brian Willard + 16yo passenger Philip Lewis; high-speed pursuit; Smith's patrol car struck/killed Lewis; §1983 14A). HOLDING: pursuit death w/o seizure -> 14A substantive due process; only purpose-to-cause-harm shocks the conscience (deliberate indifference insufficient). quotes *836 "We answer no, and hold that in such circumstances only a purpose to cause harm unrelated to the legitimate object of arrest will satisfy the element of arbitrary conduct shocking to the conscience, necessary for a due process violation." + *854 "Accordingly, we hold that high-speed chases with no intent to harm suspects physically or to worsen their legal plight do not give rise to liability under the Fourteenth Amendment, redressible by an action under §1983." good law (4A/14A boundary; Scott v. Harris later analyzes pursuit-with-seizure under 4A; cited in Kingsley). homes=[[Use of Force]] Key—Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related.
1783200000 · [S5-B11 #1] search(type=o, q="Brosseau v. Haugen QI shooting fleeing suspect vehicle clearly established", citation 543 U.S. 194) x1[cluster 137736] + get_endpoint_item(clusters/137736) x1 + read_document(137736,[0,1]) + read_document(137736,chunk2) · ok · Brosseau v. Haugen · opinion 137736 (cluster 137736) · 543 U.S. 194 (2004), No. 03-1261, decided 2004-12-13 (PER CURIAM; Breyer concur w/ Scalia+Ginsburg; Stevens dissent). HOLDING: QI for officer who shot fleeing suspect in vehicle in the back; Garner/Graham "cast at a high level of generality" & do not clearly establish answer except in obvious case; relevant fact-specific cases put conduct in "hazy border between excessive and acceptable force." Court expressed NO view on the constitutional merits, decided on QI step 2 alone. quotes p.198 "Qualified immunity shields an officer from suit when she makes a decision that, even if constitutionally deficient, reasonably misapprehends the law governing the circumstances she confronted"; p.199 "Graham and Garner, following the lead of the Fourth Amendment's text, are cast at a high level of generality"; p.201 "this area is one in which the result depends very much on the facts of each case. None of them squarely governs the case here; they do suggest that Brosseau's actions fell in the 'hazy border between excessive and acceptable force'"; p.201 "The cases by no means 'clearly establish' that Brosseau's conduct violated the Fourth Amendment." good law. home=[[Use of Force]] Key-Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related
1783200600 · [S5-B11 #2] search(type=o, q="Kisela v. Hughes QI shooting woman knife specificity per curiam", citation 584 U.S. 100) x1[cluster 4482892] + get_endpoint_item(clusters/4482892)x1[sub_op 4260145] + read_document(4260145,[0,1]) + read_document(4260145,[2,3]) · ok · Kisela v. Hughes · cluster 4482892 → lead opinion 4260145 (URL /opinion/4482892/) · 584 U.S. 100 / 138 S. Ct. 1148 (2018), No. 17-467, decided 2018-04-02 (PER CURIAM; Sotomayor dissent joined Ginsburg). HOLDING: QI for officer who shot woman holding large kitchen knife within ~6 ft of another woman after ignoring ≥2 commands to drop it; clearly-established law in force cases must be defined at high specificity; officers get QI unless precedent "squarely governs" specific facts. Court assumed arguendo a 4A violation, decided on QI. quotes 138 S.Ct. at 1152 "Qualified immunity attaches when an official's conduct does not violate clearly established statutory or constitutional rights of which a reasonable person would have known" (quoting White v. Pauly) + "not to define clearly established law at a high level of generality"; at 1153 "Use of excessive force is an area of the law 'in which the result depends very much on the facts of each case,' and thus police officers are entitled to qualified immunity unless existing precedent 'squarely governs' the specific facts at issue" (quoting Mullenix); "Garner and Graham do not by themselves create clearly established law outside an 'obvious case'"; app "far from an obvious case in which any competent officer would have known that shooting Hughes to protect Chadwick would violate the Fourth Amendment." good law. home=[[Use of Force]] Key-Progeny + [[Section 1983 Liability and Qualified Immunity]] Related
1783201200 · [S5-B11 #3] search(type=o, q="Banks v. Dretke Brady withheld paid informant due diligence", citation 540 U.S. 668) x1[cluster 131165] + get_endpoint_item(clusters/131165)x1[lead op 131165] + search_document(131165,"prosecutor may hide, defendant must seek")x1[1@56263] + read_document(131165,chunk7) + search_document(131165,"three components")x1[2@39309/40033] + read_document(131165,chunk4) · ok · Banks v. Dretke · opinion 131165 (cluster 131165) · 540 U.S. 668 (2004), No. 02-8286, decided 2004-02-24 (Ginsburg, J.; Thomas concur/dissent in part w/ Scalia). HOLDING: Brady violation where State concealed that key prosecution witness (Farr) was a paid police informant & represented it disclosed everything; defendant's failure to discover concealed evidence does not forfeit the claim. quotes p.691 three components (quoting Strickler 527 U.S. 281-282) "The evidence at issue must be favorable to the accused, either because it is exculpatory, or because it is impeaching; that evidence must have been suppressed by the State, either willfully or inadvertently; and prejudice must have ensued"; p.696 "A rule thus declaring 'prosecutor may hide, defendant must seek,' is not tenable in a system constitutionally bound to accord defendants due process"; p.698 "Nothing in Roviaro... suggests that the State can examine an informant at trial, withholding acknowledgment of his informant status in the hope that defendant will not catch on"; "It was not incumbent on Banks to prove these representations false; rather, Banks was entitled to treat the prosecutor's submissions as truthful." good law. home=[[Brady and Giglio]] Key-Progeny
1783201800 · [S5-B11 #4] search(type=o, q="United States v. Agurs Brady materiality no request exculpatory disclose", citation 427 U.S. 97) x1[cluster 109506] + search_document(109506,"reasonable doubt that did not otherwise exist")x1[2@23282/27345] + search_document(109506,"denial of the defendant's right to a fair trial")x1[1@16878] · ok · United States v. Agurs · opinion 109506 (cluster 109506) · 427 U.S. 97 (1976), No. 75-491, decided 1976-06-24 (Stevens, J.; Marshall dissent w/ Brennan). HOLDING: prosecutor's duty to disclose obviously exculpatory evidence exists even absent a request, but only material omissions are constitutional error; no-request materiality = omitted evidence "creates a reasonable doubt that did not otherwise exist." quotes p.108 "the prosecutor will not have violated his constitutional duty of disclosure unless his omission is of sufficient significance to result in the denial of the defendant's right to a fair trial"; p.112 "if the omitted evidence creates a reasonable doubt that did not otherwise exist, constitutional error has been committed. This means that the omission must be evaluated in the context of the entire record." TREATMENT=limited: Agurs's three-situation differential materiality test (incl. no-request "reasonable doubt that did not otherwise exist") SUPERSEDED by single "reasonable probability" standard of United States v. Bagley 473 U.S. 667 (1985); core disclosure-duty survives. tier 1 Binding-SCOTUS (not overruled). home=[[Brady and Giglio]] Key-Progeny; by=[[United States v. Bagley]]
1783202400 · [S5-B11 #5] search(type=o, q="Cone v. Bell Brady suppressed evidence sentencing procedural default", citation 556 U.S. 449) x1[cluster 145883] + search_document(145883,"material either to guilt or to punishment")x1[0] + search_document(145883,"evidence that is material to his guilt or punishment")x1[0] + search_document(145883,"favorable to the accused")x1[0] + search_document(145883,"material to the defendant's guilt or punishment")x1[0] + search_document(145883,"reasonable probability")x1[12] + read_document(145883,chunk7) · ok · Cone v. Bell · opinion 145883 (cluster 145883) · 556 U.S. 449 (2009), No. 07-1114, decided 2009-04-28 (Stevens, J.; Roberts concur in part; Thomas dissent w/ Alito in part). NOTE: CL html_with_citations is the SLIP opinion (paginated "556 U.S. ___" w/ slip pages); slip page + 449 = U.S. Reports page (verified: slip p.3 Part I = 452; slip p.20-21 = 469-470). HOLDING: Brady disclosure duty reaches evidence material to PUNISHMENT not only guilt; state court's mistaken "previously determined" ruling does not bar federal habeas; suppressed drug-impairment evidence not material to guilt but lower courts failed to assess materiality to death sentence → vacate/remand. quotes 556 U.S. 469 "when the State withholds from a criminal defendant evidence that is material to his guilt or punishment, it violates his right to due process of law in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment"; 470 "evidence is 'material' within the meaning of Brady when there is a reasonable probability that, had the evidence been disclosed, the result of the proceeding would have been different"; 470 n.15 "the obligation to disclose evidence favorable to the defense may arise more broadly under a prosecutor's ethical or statutory obligations"; 469 "Cone properly preserved and exhausted his Brady claim in the state court; therefore, it is not defaulted." good law. home=[[Brady and Giglio]] Key-Progeny
1783203000 · [S5-B11 #6] [QUEUE-FLAGGED RECENT 2025 - identity confirmed; distinct from Glossip v. Gross 576 U.S. 863 (2015)] search(type=o, q="Glossip v. Oklahoma Napue false testimony correct prosecutor new trial 2025", filed_after 2024-06-01) x1[3 clusters: 10776870/10339023/10339193-revisions] + get_endpoint_item(clusters/10339023)x1[sub_op 10805611] + read_document(10805611,chunk0) + read_document(10805611,chunk1) + search_document(10805611,"could in any reasonable likelihood have affected the judgment of the jury")x1[0] + search_document(10805611,"reasonable likelihood that the false testimony could have affected")x1[0] + search_document(10805611,"reasonable likelihood")x1[4] + read_document(10805611,chunk7) · ok · Glossip v. Oklahoma · cluster 10339023 → lead opinion 10805611 (URL /opinion/10339023/) · 604 U.S. 226 (2025), No. 22-7466, argued 2024-10-09, decided 2025-02-25 (Sotomayor, J.; Roberts/Kagan/Kavanaugh/Jackson join, Barrett join Part II; Barrett concur/dissent in part; Thomas dissent w/ Alito; Gorsuch recused). SLIP opinion "604 U.S. ___ (2025)" subject to formal revision; pins keyed to start page 226 + (slip op., at N). HOLDING: prosecution's knowing failure to correct key witness Sneed's false testimony (denied bipolar dx / lithium prescription) violated Napue v. Illinois 360 U.S. 264 duty to correct false testimony; Sneed was ONLY direct evidence so credibility necessarily determinative → reasonable likelihood of affecting verdict → new trial (no remand). Jurisdiction: OCCA procedural bar not independent/adequate state ground (turned on antecedent federal Napue ruling). quotes slip op. 2 Napue "held that prosecutors have a constitutional obligation to correct false testimony"; slip op.16-17 "To establish a Napue violation, a defendant must show that the prosecution knowingly solicited false testimony or knowingly allowed it 'to go uncorrected when it appear[ed]'"; "a new trial is warranted so long as the false testimony 'may have had an effect on