1783203600 · [S5-B11 #7] search(type=o, q="Mooney v. Holohan knowing use perjured testimony due process deliberate deception", citation 294 U.S. 103) x1[cluster 102372] + search_document(102372,"deliberate deception of court and jury by the presentation of testimony known to be perjured")x1[1@6721] · ok · Mooney v. Holohan · opinion 102372 (cluster 102372) · 294 U.S. 103 / 55 S. Ct. 340 (1935), decided 1935-01-21 (PER CURIAM). HOLDING: knowing prosecutorial use of perjured testimony to obtain a conviction violates 14A due process (foundational precursor of Napue/Giglio/Brady); BUT leave to file original habeas DENIED for failure to exhaust state remedies. quote p.112 "It is a requirement that cannot be deemed to be satisfied by mere notice and hearing if a State has contrived a conviction through the pretense of a trial which in truth is but used as a means of depriving a defendant of liberty through a deliberate deception of court and jury by the presentation of testimony known to be perjured. Such a contrivance by a State to procure the conviction and imprisonment of a defendant is as inconsistent with the rudimentary demands of justice as is the obtaining of a like result by intimidation"; "the action of prosecuting officers on behalf of the State... may constitute state action within the purview of the Fourteenth Amendment." good law (core principle). home=[[Brady and Giglio]] Key-Anchor (historical origin)
1783204200 · [S5-B11 #8] [ENGLISH ORIGIN — NO CL RECORD; web-discovery per L2/L6, no CL call] WebSearch x2 + WebFetch(en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entick_v_Carrington)x1 + WebSearch(pinpoint)x1 · ok · Entick v. Carrington · NO CourtListener record (correct — pre-modern English case). citation 19 How. St. Tr. 1029 (C.P. 1765); 95 Eng. Rep. 807; 2 Wils. K.B. 275; neutral [1765] EWHC KB J98. COURT = Court of Common Pleas (Lord Camden CJ) — NOTE: runbook said "King's Bench" but authoritative sources confirm COMMON PLEAS; "Wils. K.B." is the reporter series name, not the court; recorded court accurately per L1 + flagged in report. HOLDING: general warrant to break into home & seize papers for seditious libel is illegal; every invasion of private property requires positive legal authority. quotes (verbatim via Howell's State Trials / English Reports) 95 Eng. Rep. 817 / 19 How. St. Tr. 1066 "By the laws of England, every invasion of private property, be it ever so minute, is a trespass. No man can set his foot upon my ground without my licence, but he is liable to an action, though the damage be nothing"; "If it is law, it will be found in our books. If it is not to be found there, it is not law." authority_weight=Historical (tier 6); treatment good; identity_checked=true (authoritative report). home=[[Common Law Origins]] Key-Anchor(origin) + [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related
1783204800 · [S5-B11 #9] [ENGLISH ORIGIN — NO CL RECORD; web-discovery per L2/L6, no CL call] WebSearch x1 + WebFetch(press-pubs.uchicago.edu/founders/documents/amendIVs4.html)x1 · ok · Wilkes v. Wood · NO CourtListener record (correct — pre-modern English case). citation 19 How. St. Tr. 1153 (C.P. 1763); 98 Eng. Rep. 489; Lofft 1. COURT = Court of Common Pleas (Pratt CJ, later Lord Camden) — founders source explicitly "C.P. 1763"; runbook's "King's Bench" corrected per L1 + flagged in report. HOLDING: general warrant naming no offender & authorizing seizure of unidentified suspects' papers is unlawful & "totally subversive of the liberty of the subject"; jury may award exemplary damages to punish & deter (£1,000 verdict for Wilkes). quotes (verbatim via Founders' Constitution / English Reports) 98 Eng. Rep. 498-499 "If such a power is truly invested in a Secretary of State, and he can delegate this power, it certainly may affect the person and property of every man in this kingdom, and is totally subversive of the liberty of the subject"; "Damages are designed not only as a satisfaction to the injured person, but likewise as a punishment to the guilty, to deter from any such proceeding for the future, and as a proof of the detestation of the jury to the action itself." authority_weight=Historical (tier 6); treatment good; identity_checked=true (authoritative report). home=[[Common Law Origins]] Key-Anchor(origin) + [[The Warrant Requirement]] Related
1751306400 · [S6-CL/8 #1 Garner] search(type=o, citation="416 F.3d 1208") x1 -> cluster 166206 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/166206) x1 [Published, citeCount 40, sub_opinion=166206] + search_document(166206,"caretaking") x1[13] + read_document(166206, chunk 1) x1 + read_document(166206, chunks[0,4]) x1 · ok · United States v. Garner · opinion 166206 · 416 F.3d 1208 (10th Cir. 2005), decided 2005-07-27 (Henry, J.). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (man reported unconscious in a field for hours; Officer Boyd + fire dept; felon-in-possession 922(g)(1); handgun+burglary tools; AFFIRM denial of suppression). HOLDING: 3-part community-caretaking-DETENTION-OF-A-PERSON test — (1) "specific and articulable facts which ... reasonably warrant [an] intrusion" *1213; (2) "the government's interest must outweigh the individual's interest in being free from arbitrary governmental interference" *1213; (3) "the detention must last no longer than is necessary ... scope must be carefully tailored to its underlying justification" *1213; plus once-purpose-satisfied needs independent RS: "Once the officer has completed the inquiry ... must allow the person to proceed unless ... reasonable suspicion of criminal conduct" *1213. ALL pin *1213 CONFIRMED verbatim. good law (Published, 40 cites; Caniglia 2021 = home-only, does not disturb). home=[[Community Caretaking]] Key—Anchor (persons-in-public). weight=Binding in-circuit — 10th Cir.
1751306640 · [S6-CL/8 #2 Rideau] search(type=o, citation="969 F.2d 1572") x1 -> cluster 587275 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/587275) x1 [Published, citeCount 157, sub_opinions 9483168(maj)/9483169(diss)/587275(canonical combined)] + search_document([587275,9483168,9483169],"roadway") x1 + read_document(9483168, chunks[0,1]) x1 + read_document(9483168, chunk 2) x1 · ok · United States v. Rideau (Izeal Rideau, Jr.) · opinion 587275 (URL); majority text = 9483168 · 969 F.2d 1572 (5th Cir. 1992) (EN BANC), decided 1992-08-14 (Higginbotham, J.). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Beaumont TX, Officer Ellison, man intoxicated standing in roadway, backed away, patdown found gun, felon-in-possession 922(g)(1); en banc reversed panel). HOLDING (public-welfare/community-caretaking applied to a PERSON): "Police have long served the public welfare by removing intoxicated people from the public streets, where they pose a hazard to themselves and others" *1574 (cites Powell v. Texas; Cady community-caretaking); "Officer Ellison was warranted in stopping to investigate the situation and check on the man's condition" *1574; frisk: "A reasonably prudent man in Ellison's situation could have believed that his safety and that of his partner was in danger" *1574; "police officers must have specific and articulable facts indicating that their safety is in danger to justify a patdown" *1576; disposition "AFFIRMED" *1577. Pins *1574 + *1576 CONFIRMED verbatim (corrected an initial mis-merge that put the *1576 patdown-rule sentence under *1574). good law (Published, 157 cites). home=[[Community Caretaking]] Key—Progeny. weight=Binding in-circuit — 5th Cir.
1751306880 · [S6-CL/8 #3 Barnette] search(type=o, citation="5 F.4th 872") x1 -> cluster 4900401 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/4900401) x1 [Published, citeCount 49, sub_opinion 4704180] + search_document(4704180,"community caretaking") x1[7] + search_document(4704180,"probable cause to believe") x1[3] + read_document(4704180, chunks[3,4]) x1 + read_document(4704180, chunk 0) x1 · ok · Graham v. Barnette (Teresa M. Graham v. Sgt. Shannon L. Barnette et al.) · opinion 4704180 · 5 F.4th 872 (8th Cir. 2021), No. 19-2512, decided 2021-07-16 (Gruender, J.). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Minneapolis; Officers Noor/Sanchez/Sgt Barnette; warrantless home entry + seizure for mental-health eval under MN civil-commitment statute; §1983; on REMAND from SCOTUS in light of Caniglia, prior op 970 F.3d 1075 vacated). HOLDING: post-Caniglia "community caretaking" label for psychiatric seizures "seems to be a category error" (slip op. 10); "probable cause of dangerousness is the standard that must be met for a warrantless mental-health seizure to be reasonable under the Fourth Amendment" (slip op. 10); 9+ sister circuits agree (slip op. 10-11); BUT officers got qualified immunity because PC-of-dangerousness standard was NOT clearly established (some precedents suggested lower reasonable-belief). Pins = slip-op pages (CL carries slip opinion; no F.4th star pagination in text), mirrors French v. Merrill convention. good law (Published, 49 cites). home=[[Community Caretaking]] Key—Progeny/Limit. weight=Binding in-circuit — 8th Cir.
1751307120 · [S6-CL/8 #4 Walker] search(type=o, court=ca11, case_name="Walker", q="knock and talk implied license back door small departure") x1 -> cluster 2844024 (799 F.3d 1361) + get_endpoint_item(clusters/2844024) x1 [Published, citeCount 37, sub_opinion 2844024] + search_document(2844024,"departure") x1[2] + read_document(2844024, chunks[0,1]) x1 · ok · United States v. Walker (Wayne Walker) · opinion 2844024 · 799 F.3d 1361 (11th Cir. 2015), decided 2015-09-03 (PER CURIAM). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Macon GA; officers seeking Upshaw; knocked main+second door at 9pm & 11pm no answer; ~5:04 a.m. approached Honda Civic in open-sided carport, occupant=Walker; consent to enter; plain-view counterfeit $100 bills; §471; AFFIRMED denial of suppression). HOLDING: "The scope of the knock and talk exception is limited in two respects. First, it ceases where ... 'objectively reveals a purpose to conduct a search.' ... Second, ... geographically limited to the front door or a 'minor departure' from it" *1363; "approaching Walker's vehicle parked inside of his open-sided carport, instead of going to his front door, did not exceed the geographic limit ... A 'small departure from the front door ... when seeking to contact the occupants' is permissible" *1364 (quoting Taylor 458 F.3d at 1205); pre-dawn knock-and-talk "is not considered a search" so no exigency required *1364 & n.1. Pins *1363, *1364 CONFIRMED verbatim. good law (Published, 37 cites). home=[[Knock and Talk]] Recent development (role-based). weight=Binding in-circuit — 11th Cir. NOTE: cite web/CL-discovered via holding-language search (no cite supplied in task).
1751307360 · [S6-CL/8 #5 Carloss] search(type=o, citation="818 F.3d 988") x1 -> cluster 3184928 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/3184928) x1 [Published, citeCount 52, sub_opinions 9822082/83/84 + 3184893(canonical combined)] + search_document(3184893,"No Trespassing") x1[81] + search_document(3184893,"dissenting") x1[5] · ok · United States v. Carloss (Ralph Carloss) · opinion 3184893 · 818 F.3d 988 (10th Cir. 2016), No. 13-7082, decided 2016-03-11. IDENTITY CONFIRMED (tip of machine gun; "No Trespassing" signs in unenclosed yards/driveway + front-door "Posted Private Property Hunting Fishing Trapping..." sign; Wilson answered, Carloss came from back; consented to entry; AFFIRMED denial of suppression). HOLDING: "Ordinarily a police officer, like any citizen, has an implied license to approach a home, knock on the front door, and ask to speak with the occupants"; on these facts those signs "would not have conveyed to an objective officer that he could not approach the house and knock" (slip op. 1-2); inquiry "measured...by what an objective officer would have perceived" not subjective intent (slip op. 10); "just the presence of a 'No Trespassing' sign is not alone sufficient... do not have the talismanic quality" (slip op. 11); no post-Jardines authority that a sign alone revokes the license (slip op. 11). GORSUCH, Circuit Judge, DISSENTING (signs+purpose revoked license; entry=search) — illustrates split. Pins = slip-op pages (CL carries slip opinion). good law (Published, 52 cites). home=[[Knock and Talk]] Illustrates a circuit split. weight=Binding in-circuit — 10th Cir. NOTE: majority author NOT confirmed in returned text -> not asserted.
1751307600 · [S6-CL/8 #6 Lundin] search(type=o, citation="817 F.3d 1151") x1 -> cluster 3187682 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/3187682) x1 [Published, citeCount 65, sub_opinion 3187625] + search_document(3187625,"implicit license") x1[1] + read_document(3187625, chunks[0,2,3]) x1 · ok · United States v. Lundin (Eric Lundin) · opinion 3187625 · 817 F.3d 1151 (9th Cir. 2016), decided 2016-03-22 (W. Fletcher, J.). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Humboldt County/Arcata CA; ~4:00 a.m. April 23 2013; porch knock with intent to arrest after Hinds kidnap report; crashing noises -> backyard arrest -> search found 2 handguns open view; district court suppressed; AFFIRMED). HOLDING: knock-and-talk scope "coterminous with th[e] implicit license"; officers exceeded it "[f]or two reasons" — (1) TIME: "unexpected visitors are customarily expected to knock on the front door of a home only during normal waking hours"; here ~4:00 a.m. w/o evidence resident accepted visitors then or sufficiently weighty reason *1159; (2) PURPOSE: license "limited to the 'purpose of asking questions of the occupants'"; "[o]fficers who knock ... for other purposes generally exceed the scope" *1159; post-Jardines exception "depends at least in part on an officer's subjective intent" and "does not apply when officers encroach upon the curtilage of a home with the intent to arrest the occupant" *1160; officer-created exigency barred (Kentucky v. King). Pins *1159, *1160 CONFIRMED verbatim (CL has F.3d star pagination). good law (Published, 65 cites). homes=[[Knock and Talk]] Illustrates a circuit split + [[Curtilage]] Related (cross-doctrine). weight=Binding in-circuit — 9th Cir.
1751307840 · [S6-CL/8 #7 Osage] search(type=o, citation="235 F.3d 518") x1 -> cluster 160502 + get_endpoint_item(clusters/160502) x1 [Published, citeCount 34, sub_opinion 160502] + search_document(160502,"destroy or render completely useless") x1[1] + read_document(160502, chunks[0,2]) x1 · ok · United States v. Osage (David Blake Osage) · opinion 160502 · 235 F.3d 518 (10th Cir. 2000), decided 2000-12-15 (Stephen H. Anderson, J.). IDENTITY CONFIRMED (Amtrak Albuquerque; Officer Salazar; consent "yeah, I guess"; four "tamales in gravy" cans; can re-glued/felt like salt; opened with Leatherman -> methamphetamine; §841; district court denied suppression; REVERSED & REMANDED). HOLDING: scope of consent = objective reasonableness (Jimeno) *520; general consent reaches containers that could hold contraband BUT "we do not read that authority to permit the destruction of such containers" *521; "We therefore hold that, before an officer may actually destroy or render completely useless a container which would otherwise be within the scope of a permissive search, the officer must obtain explicit authorization, or have some other, lawful, basis upon which to proceed" *522. Pins *520/*521/*522 CONFIRMED verbatim (CL F.3d star pagination). good law (Published, 34 cites). home=[[Consent Searches]] Limiting. weight=Binding in-circuit — 10th Cir.
